{"title_page": "Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium", "text_new": "{{short description|Stadium in Auburn, Alabama US}} owned by the LSU TIGERS\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name      = Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium\n| image             = Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium, Tuscaloosa AL, North view 20160714 1.jpg\n| image_size        = 250\n| caption           = Bryant-Denny Stadium in [[2016 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2016]]\n| location          = 920 [[Bear Bryant|Paul W Bryant]] Drive<br>[[Tuscaloosa, Alabama]], U.S.<!-- 35401 USA -->\n| coordinates       = {{coord|33|12|28|N|87|33|2|W|display=it}}\n| pushpin_map       = USA Alabama#USA\n| pushpin_relief    = 1\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Alabama##Location in the United States\n| broke_ground      = December 1928\n| opened            = September 28, 1929\n| expanded          = 1937: East side bleachers<br>1950: 7,000+ seats<br>1961: 18,000+ seats<br>1966: 17,000+ seats<br>1988: West side upper deck<br>1998: East side upper deck<br>2006: North end zone and upper deck<br>2010: South end zone and upper deck\n| closed            = \n| demolished        = \n| owner          = \n| surface           = Grass (1929\u20131967)<br>[[AstroTurf]] (1968\u20131990)<br>Grass (1991\u2013present) \n| record_attendance = 101,821\n| tenants           = [[Alabama Crimson Tide]] ([[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]) (1929\u20131986, 1988\u2013present)<br>[[Alabama High School Athletic Association]] (2009\u2013present, odd-numbered years)\n| construction_cost = $196,000<ref>{{cite web |title=How Much Did Bryant-Denny Stadium Initially Cost to Build (in 1929)?|url=http://www.seathound.com/venue/bryant-denny-stadium-8150/question/13429/how-much-did-bryant-denny-stadium-initially-cost-to-build-in-1929/|website=SeatHound|accessdate=September 4, 2011}}</ref><br>(${{formatprice|{{Inflation|US|196000|1929}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}}<!-- dollars-->{{inflation-fn|US}})\n| architect         = Atwood and Nash, Inc., Architects and Engineers<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mellown|first1=Robert Oliver|title=The University of Alabama: A Guide to the Campus and Its Architecture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EnK9AwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|location=Tuscaloosa|publisher=The University of Alabama Press|publication-date=2013|isbn=978-0-8173-8673-3|accessdate=September 17, 2018}}</ref>\n| former_names      = Denny Stadium<br>(1929\u20131975)\n| seating_capacity  = 18,000 (1929\u20131935)<br>24,000 (1936\u20131945)<br>31,000 (1946\u20131960)<br>43,000 (1961\u20131965)<br>60,210 (1966\u20131987)<br>70,123 (1988\u20131997)<br>83,818 (1998\u20132004)<br>81,018 (2005)<br>92,138 (2006\u20132008)<br>92,012 (2009)<br>101,821 (2010\u2013present)<ref name=Official>{{cite web |title=Facilities: Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium|url=https://rolltide.com/sports/2016/6/10/facilities-bryant-denny-html.aspx|publisher=University of Alabama Department of Intercollegiate Athletics|accessdate=February 3, 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium''' is an outdoor stadium in the [[Southeastern United States|southeastern]] United States, on the campus of the [[University of Alabama]] in [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]]. It is the home field of the [[Alabama Crimson Tide]] [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|football team]] of the [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC).\n\nOpened {{Time ago|1929}} in [[1929 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1929]], it was originally named Denny Stadium in honor of [[George H. Denny]], the school's president from 1912 to 1932. In 1975, the [[Alabama Legislature|state legislature]] added longtime head coach and alumnus [[Bear Bryant|Paul \"Bear\" Bryant]] to the stadium's name. Bryant led the Tide for seven more seasons, through [[1982 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1982]], and is one of the few in [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] to have coached in a venue bearing his name.\n\nWith a [[seating capacity]] of 101,821, it is the fourth-largest stadium in the Southeastern Conference, the [[List of American football stadiums by capacity|seventh largest]] stadium in the United States and the [[List of stadiums by capacity|eighth largest]] stadium in the world.\n\n==Construction history==\n[[File:BDSNEExpansion.jpg|thumb|left|The north end zone entrance in 2007, with commemorative Alabama players statuary group on the left]]\nThe replacement for [[Denny Field (Alabama)|Denny Field]], Denny Stadium opened in [[1929 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1929]], with 6,000 in attendance for a 55\u20130 victory over [[Mississippi College Choctaws|Mississippi College]] on September 28.<ref name=\"Sept 29, 1929\">{{cite news |title=Alabama Gets 6 Touchdowns by Swift Play in First Half|first=Donald|last=Tubb|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=29A-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=gkwMAAAAIBAJ&pg=5474%2C5147177|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=September 29, 1929|accessdate=February 1, 2011}}</ref> It was officially dedicated the following week at [[homecoming]] ceremonies against [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]], a 22\u20137 Crimson Tide victory.<ref name=\"Oct 6, 1929\">{{cite news |title=12,000 See Alabama Win, 22\u20137|first=Donald|last=Tubb|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=nIA-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=BkwMAAAAIBAJ&pg=5886%2C252468|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=October 6, 1929|accessdate=February 1, 2011}}</ref> Originally, the stadium had a capacity of 12,000\u2014the lower half of the current stadium's east grandstand. However, President Denny initially envisioned a full bowl stadium capable of seating 66,000.<ref name=\"1937Expansion\">{{cite news |title=Denny Stadium|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ftY-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=10wMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6504%2C4372156|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=October 8, 1937|accessdate=April 12, 2012|page=4}}</ref>\n\nBefore the [[1937 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1937]] season, permanent seats were built along the east sideline, increasing the capacity to 24,000.<ref name=\"1937Expansion\"/><ref name=Official/> Further expansions in [[1946 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1946]] (bleachers in both end zones), [[Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1961]] (new seats in west grandstand), and [[1966 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1966]] (both end zones fully enclosed, new seats in east grandstand) raised capacity to 31,000, 43,000, and 60,210, respectively.<ref name=brushup>{{cite news |title=Brushing Up|first=Mike|last=Land|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vDUdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=paUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6296%2C3052438|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=July 15, 1983|accessdate=February 12, 2012|page=11}}</ref><ref name=Official/> An upper deck was added to the west side in [[1988 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1988]] and raised the seating by nearly 10,000 to 70,123. During the construction, the Crimson Tide played its entire [[1987 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1987]] home schedule at [[Legion Field]] in [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]], {{convert|57|mi|-1}} northeast of Bryant-Denny.<ref>{{cite news |title=Renovation at Bryant\u2013Denny Welcome News|first=Andrew|last=Carroll|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=H4o0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=lKUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6698%2C6277559|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=January 25, 1987|accessdate=February 21, 2012|page=2F}}</ref>\n\n===East upper deck (1998)===\nIn September 1995, the University of Alabama System Board of Trustees approved the construction of the east upper deck.<ref name=\"Sept 16, 1995\">{{cite news |title=Stadium Deal Gets Approval |first=Richard|last=Powell|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7TsdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MaYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4889%2C5084886|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=September 16, 1995|accessdate=February 5, 2011|page=1A}}</ref> Designed by the architectural firm of [[Heery International|Heery-Chambless-Adams]], the construction was financed by the university and $4.65 million from the city of Tuscaloosa, the city of [[Northport, Alabama|Northport]], and [[Tuscaloosa County, Alabama|Tuscaloosa County]].<ref name=\"Sept 16, 1995\"/> The localities contributed to construction costs in return for the university pledging to move all Crimson Tide home games to Bryant\u2013Denny and not play any at Legion Field.<ref name=\"Sept 16, 1995\"/>\n\nThe new upper deck provided 10,000 additional bleacher seats and 81 [[Luxury box|skyboxes]] on two levels\u201463 16-seat and 18 24-seat capacity boxes.<ref name=\"Oct 10, 1998\">{{cite news |title=Skyboxes a Popular Addition to Stadium|first=Cecil|last=Hurt|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3iEfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=UqYEAAAAIBAJ&dq=skybox%20news&pg=6747%2C1890841|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=October 10, 1998|accessdate=February 5, 2011|page=8C}}</ref> In 1999, four additional skyboxes were built to bring the total number of skyboxes to 85. A [[JumboTron]] scoreboard with video display capabilities was erected in the south end zone and was at the time the largest in collegiate sports.<ref name=\"JumboTron\">{{cite news |title=Jumbo View: Bama's Big-Screen Scoreboard is the Largest in College Football|first=Tommy|last=Deas|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=XUmZziu-z7kC&dat=19981010&printsec=frontpage&hl=en|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=October 10, 1998|accessdate=September 17, 2018|page=C1}}</ref> Additionally, a new east side entrance tower, a brick facade and reception areas for the Scholarship and A-Club level patrons was also added during the 1998 expansion.\n\nThe stadium's eastern upper deck was opened in [[1998 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1998]] and raised its official [[seating capacity]] to 83,818 at a final cost of $35 million for the addition.<ref name=\"Sept 5, 1998\">{{cite news |title=So What Else Is New?|first=Robert|last=DeWitt|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4UogAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Z6YEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5652%2C541265|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=September 5, 1998|accessdate=February 5, 2011}}</ref> The newly expanded venue debuted on September 5, and Alabama defeated [[BYU Cougars football|BYU]] 38\u201331 as running back [[Shaun Alexander]] set a Tide single-game record with five touchdowns.<ref name=\"Alexander\">{{cite news |title=Alexander spearheads Tide shootout |first=Cecil |last=Hurt |page=C1 |newspaper=Tuscaloosa News |date=September 6, 1998}}</ref>\n\n===North end zone expansion (2006)===\n[[File:Bryant-Denny Stadium by Highsmith 01.jpg|thumb|left|View of the north end zone of the stadium exterior and the Walk of Champions on gameday]]\nFollowing the [[2004 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2004]] season, the university spent approximately $47&nbsp;million on an expansion to the north end zone, which was completed days before the 2006 opener against Hawaii. It added a new upper deck to the North end zone area, complete with three different levels of skyboxes, which collectively are known as \"The Zone\", which brought the number of skyboxes in the stadium to 123. Two large display screens by [[Daktronics]] were placed in each corner of the north end zone, and [[Liquid crystal display|LCD]] ribbon screens, {{convert|3.5|ft}} tall by {{convert|422|ft}} wide, were placed along the front edge of the east and west upper decks.\n\nMassive changes were made to the grounds of the north side of the stadium with the addition of a [[:Category:Walks of fame|Walk]] of Champions.  Building the Walk of Champions required the demolition of the [[Delta Kappa Epsilon]] fraternity house and the [[Grading (engineering)|grading]] of the hill it sat upon. The Walk of Champions comprises a brick plaza leading from University Boulevard to the north end zone entrances.  The plaza features 16 granite monuments set into the walkway commemorating the Crimson Tide's SEC and national championship teams throughout the years. Along the west side of the plaza are five roughly {{convert|2000|lb|adj=on}}, {{convert|9|ft|adj=on}} tall bronze statues, one for each Alabama football coach who has led the Crimson Tide to a national championship. Each statue has a semicircular wall behind it bearing the coach's name and the year(s) that he led the team to a national championship. The first four statues, unveiled during the opening in 2006, included [[Wallace Wade]], [[Frank Thomas (American football)|Frank Thomas]], [[Bear Bryant|Paul \"Bear\" Bryant]], and [[Gene Stallings]].<ref name=\"gadstimesjun2006\">{{cite news |title=Bryant\u2013Denny Undergoing Monumental Change|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1891&dat=20060629&id=qp1GAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3P0MAAAAIBAJ&pg=2100,2884194|newspaper=[[The Gadsden Times]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=June 29, 2006|accessdate=December 25, 2012}}</ref> The fifth statue, that of [[Nick Saban]], was unveiled prior to the A-Day game on April 16, 2011.  It commemorates Saban guiding Alabama to its 13th National Championship with a 37\u201321 win over the [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas Longhorns]].\n\nFinally, there is a bronze statuary group of two anonymous Alabama football players at the entrance to the north end zone, with the one on the left holding a large Alabama Crimson Tide flag upright on a flagpole. This player is wearing the number 18 and a helmet, with the player on the right wearing the number 92 and pointing into the distance. The jersey numbers represent 1892, the first season of Crimson Tide football.<ref name=\"gadstimesjun2006\"/>\n\nThe north end zone was opened for the [[2006 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2006]] season opener versus [[2006 Hawaii Warriors football team|Hawaii]], which set a new record attendance of 92,138. The Crimson Tide was victorious, 25\u201317.<ref>{{cite web |title=Late Defensive Stand Helps Tide Hold Off Game Hawaii|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=262450333|work=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=September 2, 2006|accessdate=October 7, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===South end zone expansion (2010)===\n[[File:Bryant-Denny south 2010-09-04 Altered.jpg|thumb|right|Exterior of the newly-expanded south end zone in 2010]]\n[[File:Bryant Denny 2 9-4-10.jpg|thumb|right|[[LED]] screens in the south end zone in 2010]]\nThe University of Alabama Board of Trustees approved a study for further expansion of Bryant\u2013Denny on September 19, 2008.<ref>{{cite news |title=UA Trustees Approve Unitial Study for Bryant-Denny stadium Expansion|first=Kyle|last=Fondren|url=http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20080919/WVUA01/809190297|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=September 19, 2008|accessdate=September 17, 2018}}</ref> The Physical Properties Committee of the University of Alabama Board of Trustees heard a presentation from the UA athletic department on November 13, 2008 regarding the proposed $80.6 million expansion of the south end zone upper deck and suite level of Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium.  The proposed expansion would bring the stadium's capacity to approximately 101,600, therefore making it the second largest stadium in the Southeastern Conference (SEC), and the fifth largest stadium in college football.<ref>{{cite web |title=Offeseason Pigskinpalooza: College Football's Megastadiums|first=D. J.|last=Gallo|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/page2/story?page=gallo/100715_nfl_college_football_offseason|work=[[ESPN]]|date=July 15, 2010|accessdate=November 18, 2010}}</ref> The committee unanimously approved the project to move into the third of four stages, the fourth being final approval to begin construction.<ref>{{cite news |title=$80.6M Budget Approved for Stadium Expansion|first=Brett|last=Bralley|url=http://www.cw.ua.edu/80.6m_budget_approved_for_stadium_expansion|newspaper=[[The Crimson White]]|location=University of Alabama|date=November 14, 2008|accessdate=November 18, 2008}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nOn February 6, 2009, the university's Board of Trustees voted unanimously and without discussion to give the final approval for construction to commence on the south end zone expansion. With the approval of the Board of Trustees, construction began in the Spring of 2009 and continued throughout the 2009 football season.<ref>{{cite news |title=It's Official|first=Ian|last=Rapport|url=http://blog.al.com/rapsheet/2009/02/its_official_bryantdenny_will.html|newspaper=[[The Birmingham News]]|date=February 6, 2009|accessdate=February 6, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |title=Board of Trustees Officially Approves Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium South End Zone Expansion Project|url=http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/020609aaa.html|publisher=University of Alabama Department of Intercollegiate Athletics|date=February 6, 2009|accessdate=February 7, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090414004253/http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/020609aaa.html|archivedate=April 14, 2009}}</ref> The expansion was finished in time for the first game of the team's [[2010 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2010 season]].\n\n''The Tuscaloosa News'' reported on April 17, 2009 that due to the economic climate and resultant lowered construction costs, the stadium expansion cost $15 million less than expected, coming in around $65.6 million.<ref>{{cite news |title=UA Stadium Expansion Cheaper Than Expected|first=Adam|last=Jones|url=http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20090417/NEWS/904169969|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=April 17, 2009|accessdate=April 19, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe expanded south end zone now includes a two level South Zone club with a total of 1,700 seats and 36 skyboxes to bring the total number of skyboxes in Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium to 159, as well as  an 8,500 seat upper deck. The entire stadium's audio/visual system was upgraded to include two new video boards in both corners of the south end zone.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Mal Moore Announces Request For Approval Of South End Zone Project|url=http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/020309aaa.html|publisher=University of Alabama Department of Intercollegiate Athletics|date=February 6, 2009|accessdate=February 7, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120909034948/http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/020309aaa.html|archivedate=September 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the [[2009 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2009]] season, the large south scoreboard was disassembled to make way for the construction of the new stadium expansion. During this process, some welding equipment started a fire that burned the inside of the scoreboard.<ref>{{cite news |title=Small Fire Strikes Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium Scoreboad|first=Gentry|last=Estes|url=http://blog.al.com/bamabeat/2009/02/small_fire_strikes_bryantdenny.html|newspaper=[[Press-Register]]|location=Mobile|date=February 19, 2009|accessdate=November 22, 2009}}</ref> Also, during this time, four new play clocks and down/distance indicators were installed (one behind each corner of the end zones) and a new LED game clock was placed behind the south goalpost.\n\nThe expansion was completed in mid-summer [[2010 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2010]] and held an official capacity of 101,821 making it the fifth largest college football stadium in the country. The new seats were all sold out quickly for the entire 2010 football season. Subsequent expansions included stores and other extra amenities on the bottom of the end zone.\n\n===2020s renovations===\nAs part of a larger, 10-year $600 million plan to upgrade campus athletic facilities, the University is planning $92.5 million in upgrades to the stadium, including new social spaces, improved circulation, additional premium seating and upgraded spaces for athletes and recruits. The Walk of Champions will be extended into a new game day locker room via a new tunnel clad with video boards. The project will be funded with $48.4 million in bonds and $35 million from the Crimson Tide Foundation, the fundraising arm of UA athletics. Construction began shortly after the [[2019 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2019 season]].<ref>{{cite news|work=Tuscaloosa News|url=https://www.tuscaloosanews.com/news/20180921/bryant-denny-stadium-to-undergo-75-million-renovation|title=Bryant-Denny Stadium to undergo $75 million renovation|date=21 September 2018|accessdate=3 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=AL.com|url=https://www.al.com/alabamafootball/2019/06/big-changes-made-to-bryant-denny-stadium-renovation-plan.html|title=Big changes made to Bryant-Denny Stadium renovation plan|date=4 June 2019|accessdate=6 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nNew LED lights for the stadium were unveiled on the night of August 12, 2019, including a crimson-hued light display by the new installations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tuscaloosanews.com/news/20190813/bryant-denny-stadium-has-new-look|title=Bryant-Denny Stadium has new look|date=13 August 2019|accessdate=14 August 2019|work=Tuscaloosa News}}</ref>\n\n==Football lore==\n[[File:WalkofChampions 2010-11-26.jpg|thumb|left|The Walk of Champions prior to the 2010 [[Iron Bowl]]]]\nSince its opening in [[1929 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1929]] through [[2010 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2010]], the Crimson Tide owns a {{Winning percentage|212|50|3|record=y}} record at Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium.<ref name=\"BDS_all-time\">{{cite web |url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/alab/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/history-awards.pdf |title=Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium Year-By-Year Record |work=2010 Alabama Football Media Guide |publisher=University of Alabama Athletic Department |page=138 |accessdate=February 3, 2011 |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523102902/http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/alab/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/history-awards.pdf |archivedate=May 23, 2011 }}</ref> Bear Bryant is the leader in wins at the stadium, with an all-time record of {{Winning percentage|72|2|record=y}} in his quarter century as Tide head coach.<ref name=\"BDS_all-time\"/>\n\nDespite its success at Bryant\u2013Denny, most of Alabama's \"home\" football history from the 1920s through the 1980s occurred at Birmingham's Legion Field.<ref name=\"Legion_all-time\">{{cite web |title=2010 Alabama Football Media Guide|trans-title=Alabama Football at Legion Field|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/alab/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/history-awards.pdf|publisher=University of Alabama Department of Intercollegiate Athletics|accessdate=February 3, 2011|pages=141\u2013142|format=PDF|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523102902/http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/alab/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/history-awards.pdf|archivedate=May 23, 2011}}</ref> Well into the 1980s, Legion Field seated almost 20,000 more people than Bryant-Denny. As such, until the late 1990s, Legion Field hosted most of Alabama's important home games. The most notable of these games was the [[Iron Bowl]] with rival [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]]. Legion Field was considered a neutral site from 1948 through 1987. When the Iron Bowl became a home-and-home series in 1988, Alabama continued to host its home games in the series at Legion Field in even-numbered years through 1998. The Crimson Tide hosted Tennessee in odd-numbered years in Birmingham until 1999, and LSU in even-numbered years from 1964 through 1986, except for 1980. Usually, Bryant\u2013Denny hosted three or four games per season, mostly non-conference games, although the Tide always played Mississippi State in Tuscaloosa, save for 1987, due to the close distance between Tuscaloosa and [[Starkville, Mississippi|Starkville]]. However, in 1998, when Bryant\u2013Denny was expanded to a capacity exceeding Legion Field, the more important home games started to move to Bryant\u2013Denny, culminating with the move of the Tennessee series to Tuscaloosa in 1999 and the Iron Bowl a year later.<ref name=\"March 6, 1999\">{{cite news |title=Vols Due in Fall, AU in 2000|first=Cecil|last=Hurt|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=6ckdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VqYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6026%2C631746|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=March 6, 1999|accessdate=February 3, 2011|page=1}}</ref> From 1998 to 2003, Alabama continued to play two or three minor games in Birmingham. Finally, in 2003, Alabama played its final game at Legion Field against the [[South Florida Bulls]], and now Bryant\u2013Denny is the sole home of Alabama football.<ref name=\"Legion_all-time\"/>\n\n[[File:BDSfromDennyChimes.JPG|thumb|View of the northern side of the stadium and [[Tailgate party|tailgaters]] as seen from the [[Denny Chimes]] vicinity of [[University of Alabama Quad|The Quad]] in 2008.]]\nHowever, despite the majority of past big games being played at Legion Field, Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium has hosted many memorable games, such as the 1994 shootout between Alabama's [[Jay Barker]] and Georgia's [[Eric Zeier]], Marvin Constant's goal-line stop against [[1999 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]] quarterback Josh Booty as time expired in 1999, [[Tyrone Prothro]]'s reception over the back of Southern Miss defensive back Jasper Faulk in 2005, a 31\u20133 victory over No. 5 Florida in 2005, the [[Roman Harper]]-forced fumble against [[2005 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]] in 2005 that helped the Crimson Tide to victory, Alabama's 36\u20130 shutout victory against Auburn in 2008 thus breaking the six-game losing streak and first ever [[Iron Bowl]] victory in Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium, [[Terrence Cody]]'s field goal block against [[2009 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]] as time expired in 2009, and their 28-27 loss to the [[2010 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn Tigers]] known as the Camback where the Tide squandered a 24-0 lead against the Tigers. In recent years, Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium has become a feared place to play again.  Also Bryant-Denny has been put on many lists ranking it one of the best places to watch football. [[NCAA Football 11]] ranked Alabama's Bryant\u2013Denny as the fourth toughest place to play in the nation and third in the SEC behind [[Ben Hill Griffin Stadium|Florida]] and [[Tiger Stadium (LSU)|LSU]]. ''Sporting News'' ranks it first while Bleacher Report has it ranked as the 5th toughest and the 2nd best stadium in the country.<ref>{{cite web |title=College Football Rankings: 25 Best College Football Game Day Experiences|first=Wes|last=O'Donnell|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/592904-25-best-college-football-game-day-experiences/page/25|work=[[Bleacher Report]]|date=February 1, 2011|accessdate=September 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Field design==\n{{Panorama\n |image      = File:Bryant-Denny 10-22-11.jpg\n |fullwidth  = 7136\n |fullheight = 2392\n |caption    = The interior of Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium (south end zone, left) during a [[2011 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2011]] Alabama game versus [[2011 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]].\n |height     = 200\n}}\n\nUntil the turn of the millennium, the field at Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium had only the necessary markings required for play. As more and more stadiums began to add other designs to the field, such as logos, Alabama chose to remain traditional with the field design. In fact, even into the 2002 season, Bryant\u2013Denny still had no logo at midfield and no logos at the 25-yard lines, which are now commonplace in many stadiums. The end zone design simply consisted of \"ALABAMA\" in a white, block-style font. During the 1992 season, however, a special logo was used at midfield to commemorate the centennial season of Alabama football.\n\nDuring the 2002 season, however, a large white script \u201cA\u201d was added to midfield. The field design underwent full-scale changes beginning with the 2004 season. At midfield, the large white script \u201cA\u201d was replaced with the crimson script \u201cA\u201d logo, encircled by a crimson ring which has \"Alabama Crimson Tide\" written around it. In addition, the end zone designs were changed to a crimson block-style font outlined in white.\n\nFor the 2006 season, two identical logos commemorating the 175th anniversary of the university were also added to the field on the 25-yard lines. One was added on the south end of the stadium, on the west side of the playing field, while the other was on the north end of the stadium, on the east side of the playing field.\n\n[[File:2011 houndstooth ribbon on the field at Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium.jpg|thumb|right|alt=American football field with a houndstooth awareness ribbon painted on it.|left|Detail of the [[houndstooth]] [[awareness ribbon]] painted on-field in remembrance of the victims and damage of the April 2011 tornado.]]\nFor the 2007 season, two identical logos commemorating the 75th anniversary of the founding of the [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC) were added to home field of every SEC team. These were in the same places as the 175th logos were during the 2006 season.\n\nFor the 2008 season, two identical SEC logos were added to the home field of every SEC team. Alabama\u2019s crimson was used as the primary color for the logos at Bryant\u2013Denny. These logos were located in the same places as the previous logos and remain there today.\n\nFor the 2009 A-day game, the end zones were changed back to the original white block-style font that was used prior to the 2004 season, except that the background was shaded crimson. The north end zone displayed \"ALABAMA\", while the south end zone displayed \"CRIMSON TIDE\".  This design layout has remained in use since the 2009 season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Photo of Bryant-Denny Stadium Design for the 2009 A-day Game|url=http://i40.tinypic.com/dnp09e.jpg|publisher=Tiny Pic}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2011 season, two identical [[houndstooth]] [[awareness ribbon]]s recognizing the ongoing relief efforts following the [[2011 Tuscaloosa\u2013Birmingham tornado|April 27, 2011 tornado]] were added to the field on the 25 yard lines.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bryant\u2013Denny Unveils Tornado Ribbons|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/news?slug=rivals-1259179|work=[[Rivals.com|Rivals]]|date=September 1, 2011|accessdate=September 4, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Awareness\">{{cite news |title=Alabama's Opener Against Kent State Could Help Healing in Tuscaloosa|first=Izzy|last=Gould|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2011/09/alabamas_opener_against_kent_s.html|newspaper=[[Press-Register]]|location=Mobile|date=September 2, 2011|accessdate=March 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Locker rooms==\nIn 2008, the visitors' locker room was officially named \"The Fail Room\" after alumnus and donor [[James M. Fail]]. He commented, \"Earlier this year, when I saw the visitors' locker room as a potential naming right, I figured it was the most appropriate opportunity I would ever have to use my name.\"<ref>{{cite press release |title=Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium Visitors Locker Room Named for James M. Fail|url=http://www.rolltide.com/genrel/121508aab.html|publisher=University of Alabama Department of Intercollegiate Athletics|date=December 15, 2008|accessdate=December 15, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==High school championships==\nBeginning in 2009, Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium and [[Auburn University]]'s [[Jordan\u2013Hare Stadium]] became the homes of the [[Alabama High School Athletic Association]] state football championship games, known as the Super Seven. Bryant-Denny hosts the Super Seven in odd-numbered years, with Jordan\u2013Hare taking the games in even-numbered years. Previously, the Super Six was held at [[Legion Field]] in [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]].\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"150px\">\nBDS Night (Iron Bowl 2006).jpg|[[Iron Bowl]] [[2006 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2006]]\nBryant-Denny scoreboard.jpg|The old south end zone scoreboard in 2007. Installed in 1998, the JumboTron was removed during 2009-2010 renovations\nBryant Denny Stadium Walk of Champions.jpg|The Walk of Champions in 2008\nBDS West 2010-11-26.jpg|Looking west in [[2010 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2010]]\nBryant-Denny Stadium panoramic 2010-10-02.jpg|Panoramic view of interior, 2010\nStatues of Coaches at Bryant-Danny-Stadium.jpg|The \"Coaches Walk\" alongside the Walk of Champions in 2012. It features statues to prominent [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Crimson Tide football]] head coaches\nBryantDennyStadiumApril2013Tuscaloosa.png|Bryant-Denny Stadium in April 2013\nBryant Denny Stadium.jpg|Interior at night during off-season, 2015\nPresident Trump and First Lady Melania Trump in Alabama (49048699303).jpg|45th President of the United States [[Donald Trump]] at Bryant-Denny, November 2019\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.rolltide.com/sports/2016/6/10/facilities-bryant-denny-html.aspx Bryant-Denny Stadium page on Rolltide.com]\n\n{{Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{University of Alabama}}\n{{Southeastern Conference football venue navbox}}\n{{Alabama college football venues}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bryant-Denny Stadium}}\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football venues]]\n[[Category:American football venues in Alabama]]\n[[Category:College football venues]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Tuscaloosa, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1929]]\n[[Category:1929 establishments in Alabama]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Stadium in Auburn, Alabama US}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name      = Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium\n| image             = Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium, Tuscaloosa AL, North view 20160714 1.jpg\n| image_size        = 250\n| caption           = Bryant-Denny Stadium in [[2016 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2016]]\n| location          = 920 [[Bear Bryant|Paul W Bryant]] Drive<br>[[Tuscaloosa, Alabama]], U.S.<!-- 35401 USA -->\n| coordinates       = {{coord|33|12|28|N|87|33|2|W|display=it}}\n| pushpin_map       = USA Alabama#USA\n| pushpin_relief    = 1\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Alabama##Location in the United States\n| broke_ground      = December 1928\n| opened            = September 28, 1929\n| expanded          = 1937: East side bleachers<br>1950: 7,000+ seats<br>1961: 18,000+ seats<br>1966: 17,000+ seats<br>1988: West side upper deck<br>1998: East side upper deck<br>2006: North end zone and upper deck<br>2010: South end zone and upper deck\n| closed            = \n| demolished        = \n| owner          = \n| surface           = Grass (1929\u20131967)<br>[[AstroTurf]] (1968\u20131990)<br>Grass (1991\u2013present) \n| record_attendance = 101,821\n| tenants           = [[Alabama Crimson Tide]] ([[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]) (1929\u20131986, 1988\u2013present)<br>[[Alabama High School Athletic Association]] (2009\u2013present, odd-numbered years)\n| construction_cost = $196,000<ref>{{cite web |title=How Much Did Bryant-Denny Stadium Initially Cost to Build (in 1929)?|url=http://www.seathound.com/venue/bryant-denny-stadium-8150/question/13429/how-much-did-bryant-denny-stadium-initially-cost-to-build-in-1929/|website=SeatHound|accessdate=September 4, 2011}}</ref><br>(${{formatprice|{{Inflation|US|196000|1929}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}}<!-- dollars-->{{inflation-fn|US}})\n| architect         = Atwood and Nash, Inc., Architects and Engineers<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mellown|first1=Robert Oliver|title=The University of Alabama: A Guide to the Campus and Its Architecture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EnK9AwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|location=Tuscaloosa|publisher=The University of Alabama Press|publication-date=2013|isbn=978-0-8173-8673-3|accessdate=September 17, 2018}}</ref>\n| former_names      = Denny Stadium<br>(1929\u20131975)\n| seating_capacity  = 18,000 (1929\u20131935)<br>24,000 (1936\u20131945)<br>31,000 (1946\u20131960)<br>43,000 (1961\u20131965)<br>60,210 (1966\u20131987)<br>70,123 (1988\u20131997)<br>83,818 (1998\u20132004)<br>81,018 (2005)<br>92,138 (2006\u20132008)<br>92,012 (2009)<br>101,821 (2010\u2013present)<ref name=Official>{{cite web |title=Facilities: Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium|url=https://rolltide.com/sports/2016/6/10/facilities-bryant-denny-html.aspx|publisher=University of Alabama Department of Intercollegiate Athletics|accessdate=February 3, 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium''' is an outdoor stadium in the [[Southeastern United States|southeastern]] United States, on the campus of the [[University of Alabama]] in [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]]. It is the home field of the [[Alabama Crimson Tide]] [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|football team]] of the [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC).\n\nOpened {{Time ago|1929}} in [[1929 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1929]], it was originally named Denny Stadium in honor of [[George H. Denny]], the school's president from 1912 to 1932. In 1975, the [[Alabama Legislature|state legislature]] added longtime head coach and alumnus [[Bear Bryant|Paul \"Bear\" Bryant]] to the stadium's name. Bryant led the Tide for seven more seasons, through [[1982 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1982]], and is one of the few in [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] to have coached in a venue bearing his name.\n\nWith a [[seating capacity]] of 101,821, it is the fourth-largest stadium in the Southeastern Conference, the [[List of American football stadiums by capacity|seventh largest]] stadium in the United States and the [[List of stadiums by capacity|eighth largest]] stadium in the world.\n\n==Construction history==\n[[File:BDSNEExpansion.jpg|thumb|left|The north end zone entrance in 2007, with commemorative Alabama players statuary group on the left]]\nThe replacement for [[Denny Field (Alabama)|Denny Field]], Denny Stadium opened in [[1929 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1929]], with 6,000 in attendance for a 55\u20130 victory over [[Mississippi College Choctaws|Mississippi College]] on September 28.<ref name=\"Sept 29, 1929\">{{cite news |title=Alabama Gets 6 Touchdowns by Swift Play in First Half|first=Donald|last=Tubb|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=29A-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=gkwMAAAAIBAJ&pg=5474%2C5147177|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=September 29, 1929|accessdate=February 1, 2011}}</ref> It was officially dedicated the following week at [[homecoming]] ceremonies against [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]], a 22\u20137 Crimson Tide victory.<ref name=\"Oct 6, 1929\">{{cite news |title=12,000 See Alabama Win, 22\u20137|first=Donald|last=Tubb|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=nIA-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=BkwMAAAAIBAJ&pg=5886%2C252468|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=October 6, 1929|accessdate=February 1, 2011}}</ref> Originally, the stadium had a capacity of 12,000\u2014the lower half of the current stadium's east grandstand. However, President Denny initially envisioned a full bowl stadium capable of seating 66,000.<ref name=\"1937Expansion\">{{cite news |title=Denny Stadium|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ftY-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=10wMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6504%2C4372156|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=October 8, 1937|accessdate=April 12, 2012|page=4}}</ref>\n\nBefore the [[1937 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1937]] season, permanent seats were built along the east sideline, increasing the capacity to 24,000.<ref name=\"1937Expansion\"/><ref name=Official/> Further expansions in [[1946 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1946]] (bleachers in both end zones), [[Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1961]] (new seats in west grandstand), and [[1966 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1966]] (both end zones fully enclosed, new seats in east grandstand) raised capacity to 31,000, 43,000, and 60,210, respectively.<ref name=brushup>{{cite news |title=Brushing Up|first=Mike|last=Land|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vDUdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=paUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6296%2C3052438|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=July 15, 1983|accessdate=February 12, 2012|page=11}}</ref><ref name=Official/> An upper deck was added to the west side in [[1988 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1988]] and raised the seating by nearly 10,000 to 70,123. During the construction, the Crimson Tide played its entire [[1987 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1987]] home schedule at [[Legion Field]] in [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]], {{convert|57|mi|-1}} northeast of Bryant-Denny.<ref>{{cite news |title=Renovation at Bryant\u2013Denny Welcome News|first=Andrew|last=Carroll|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=H4o0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=lKUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6698%2C6277559|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=January 25, 1987|accessdate=February 21, 2012|page=2F}}</ref>\n\n===East upper deck (1998)===\nIn September 1995, the University of Alabama System Board of Trustees approved the construction of the east upper deck.<ref name=\"Sept 16, 1995\">{{cite news |title=Stadium Deal Gets Approval |first=Richard|last=Powell|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7TsdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MaYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4889%2C5084886|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=September 16, 1995|accessdate=February 5, 2011|page=1A}}</ref> Designed by the architectural firm of [[Heery International|Heery-Chambless-Adams]], the construction was financed by the university and $4.65 million from the city of Tuscaloosa, the city of [[Northport, Alabama|Northport]], and [[Tuscaloosa County, Alabama|Tuscaloosa County]].<ref name=\"Sept 16, 1995\"/> The localities contributed to construction costs in return for the university pledging to move all Crimson Tide home games to Bryant\u2013Denny and not play any at Legion Field.<ref name=\"Sept 16, 1995\"/>\n\nThe new upper deck provided 10,000 additional bleacher seats and 81 [[Luxury box|skyboxes]] on two levels\u201463 16-seat and 18 24-seat capacity boxes.<ref name=\"Oct 10, 1998\">{{cite news |title=Skyboxes a Popular Addition to Stadium|first=Cecil|last=Hurt|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3iEfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=UqYEAAAAIBAJ&dq=skybox%20news&pg=6747%2C1890841|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=October 10, 1998|accessdate=February 5, 2011|page=8C}}</ref> In 1999, four additional skyboxes were built to bring the total number of skyboxes to 85. A [[JumboTron]] scoreboard with video display capabilities was erected in the south end zone and was at the time the largest in collegiate sports.<ref name=\"JumboTron\">{{cite news |title=Jumbo View: Bama's Big-Screen Scoreboard is the Largest in College Football|first=Tommy|last=Deas|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=XUmZziu-z7kC&dat=19981010&printsec=frontpage&hl=en|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=October 10, 1998|accessdate=September 17, 2018|page=C1}}</ref> Additionally, a new east side entrance tower, a brick facade and reception areas for the Scholarship and A-Club level patrons was also added during the 1998 expansion.\n\nThe stadium's eastern upper deck was opened in [[1998 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1998]] and raised its official [[seating capacity]] to 83,818 at a final cost of $35 million for the addition.<ref name=\"Sept 5, 1998\">{{cite news |title=So What Else Is New?|first=Robert|last=DeWitt|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4UogAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Z6YEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5652%2C541265|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=September 5, 1998|accessdate=February 5, 2011}}</ref> The newly expanded venue debuted on September 5, and Alabama defeated [[BYU Cougars football|BYU]] 38\u201331 as running back [[Shaun Alexander]] set a Tide single-game record with five touchdowns.<ref name=\"Alexander\">{{cite news |title=Alexander spearheads Tide shootout |first=Cecil |last=Hurt |page=C1 |newspaper=Tuscaloosa News |date=September 6, 1998}}</ref>\n\n===North end zone expansion (2006)===\n[[File:Bryant-Denny Stadium by Highsmith 01.jpg|thumb|left|View of the north end zone of the stadium exterior and the Walk of Champions on gameday]]\nFollowing the [[2004 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2004]] season, the university spent approximately $47&nbsp;million on an expansion to the north end zone, which was completed days before the 2006 opener against Hawaii. It added a new upper deck to the North end zone area, complete with three different levels of skyboxes, which collectively are known as \"The Zone\", which brought the number of skyboxes in the stadium to 123. Two large display screens by [[Daktronics]] were placed in each corner of the north end zone, and [[Liquid crystal display|LCD]] ribbon screens, {{convert|3.5|ft}} tall by {{convert|422|ft}} wide, were placed along the front edge of the east and west upper decks.\n\nMassive changes were made to the grounds of the north side of the stadium with the addition of a [[:Category:Walks of fame|Walk]] of Champions.  Building the Walk of Champions required the demolition of the [[Delta Kappa Epsilon]] fraternity house and the [[Grading (engineering)|grading]] of the hill it sat upon. The Walk of Champions comprises a brick plaza leading from University Boulevard to the north end zone entrances.  The plaza features 16 granite monuments set into the walkway commemorating the Crimson Tide's SEC and national championship teams throughout the years. Along the west side of the plaza are five roughly {{convert|2000|lb|adj=on}}, {{convert|9|ft|adj=on}} tall bronze statues, one for each Alabama football coach who has led the Crimson Tide to a national championship. Each statue has a semicircular wall behind it bearing the coach's name and the year(s) that he led the team to a national championship. The first four statues, unveiled during the opening in 2006, included [[Wallace Wade]], [[Frank Thomas (American football)|Frank Thomas]], [[Bear Bryant|Paul \"Bear\" Bryant]], and [[Gene Stallings]].<ref name=\"gadstimesjun2006\">{{cite news |title=Bryant\u2013Denny Undergoing Monumental Change|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1891&dat=20060629&id=qp1GAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3P0MAAAAIBAJ&pg=2100,2884194|newspaper=[[The Gadsden Times]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=June 29, 2006|accessdate=December 25, 2012}}</ref> The fifth statue, that of [[Nick Saban]], was unveiled prior to the A-Day game on April 16, 2011.  It commemorates Saban guiding Alabama to its 13th National Championship with a 37\u201321 win over the [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas Longhorns]].\n\nFinally, there is a bronze statuary group of two anonymous Alabama football players at the entrance to the north end zone, with the one on the left holding a large Alabama Crimson Tide flag upright on a flagpole. This player is wearing the number 18 and a helmet, with the player on the right wearing the number 92 and pointing into the distance. The jersey numbers represent 1892, the first season of Crimson Tide football.<ref name=\"gadstimesjun2006\"/>\n\nThe north end zone was opened for the [[2006 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2006]] season opener versus [[2006 Hawaii Warriors football team|Hawaii]], which set a new record attendance of 92,138. The Crimson Tide was victorious, 25\u201317.<ref>{{cite web |title=Late Defensive Stand Helps Tide Hold Off Game Hawaii|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=262450333|work=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=September 2, 2006|accessdate=October 7, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===South end zone expansion (2010)===\n[[File:Bryant-Denny south 2010-09-04 Altered.jpg|thumb|right|Exterior of the newly-expanded south end zone in 2010]]\n[[File:Bryant Denny 2 9-4-10.jpg|thumb|right|[[LED]] screens in the south end zone in 2010]]\nThe University of Alabama Board of Trustees approved a study for further expansion of Bryant\u2013Denny on September 19, 2008.<ref>{{cite news |title=UA Trustees Approve Unitial Study for Bryant-Denny stadium Expansion|first=Kyle|last=Fondren|url=http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20080919/WVUA01/809190297|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=September 19, 2008|accessdate=September 17, 2018}}</ref> The Physical Properties Committee of the University of Alabama Board of Trustees heard a presentation from the UA athletic department on November 13, 2008 regarding the proposed $80.6 million expansion of the south end zone upper deck and suite level of Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium.  The proposed expansion would bring the stadium's capacity to approximately 101,600, therefore making it the second largest stadium in the Southeastern Conference (SEC), and the fifth largest stadium in college football.<ref>{{cite web |title=Offeseason Pigskinpalooza: College Football's Megastadiums|first=D. J.|last=Gallo|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/page2/story?page=gallo/100715_nfl_college_football_offseason|work=[[ESPN]]|date=July 15, 2010|accessdate=November 18, 2010}}</ref> The committee unanimously approved the project to move into the third of four stages, the fourth being final approval to begin construction.<ref>{{cite news |title=$80.6M Budget Approved for Stadium Expansion|first=Brett|last=Bralley|url=http://www.cw.ua.edu/80.6m_budget_approved_for_stadium_expansion|newspaper=[[The Crimson White]]|location=University of Alabama|date=November 14, 2008|accessdate=November 18, 2008}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nOn February 6, 2009, the university's Board of Trustees voted unanimously and without discussion to give the final approval for construction to commence on the south end zone expansion. With the approval of the Board of Trustees, construction began in the Spring of 2009 and continued throughout the 2009 football season.<ref>{{cite news |title=It's Official|first=Ian|last=Rapport|url=http://blog.al.com/rapsheet/2009/02/its_official_bryantdenny_will.html|newspaper=[[The Birmingham News]]|date=February 6, 2009|accessdate=February 6, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |title=Board of Trustees Officially Approves Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium South End Zone Expansion Project|url=http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/020609aaa.html|publisher=University of Alabama Department of Intercollegiate Athletics|date=February 6, 2009|accessdate=February 7, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090414004253/http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/020609aaa.html|archivedate=April 14, 2009}}</ref> The expansion was finished in time for the first game of the team's [[2010 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2010 season]].\n\n''The Tuscaloosa News'' reported on April 17, 2009 that due to the economic climate and resultant lowered construction costs, the stadium expansion cost $15 million less than expected, coming in around $65.6 million.<ref>{{cite news |title=UA Stadium Expansion Cheaper Than Expected|first=Adam|last=Jones|url=http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20090417/NEWS/904169969|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=April 17, 2009|accessdate=April 19, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe expanded south end zone now includes a two level South Zone club with a total of 1,700 seats and 36 skyboxes to bring the total number of skyboxes in Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium to 159, as well as  an 8,500 seat upper deck. The entire stadium's audio/visual system was upgraded to include two new video boards in both corners of the south end zone.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Mal Moore Announces Request For Approval Of South End Zone Project|url=http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/020309aaa.html|publisher=University of Alabama Department of Intercollegiate Athletics|date=February 6, 2009|accessdate=February 7, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120909034948/http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/020309aaa.html|archivedate=September 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the [[2009 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2009]] season, the large south scoreboard was disassembled to make way for the construction of the new stadium expansion. During this process, some welding equipment started a fire that burned the inside of the scoreboard.<ref>{{cite news |title=Small Fire Strikes Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium Scoreboad|first=Gentry|last=Estes|url=http://blog.al.com/bamabeat/2009/02/small_fire_strikes_bryantdenny.html|newspaper=[[Press-Register]]|location=Mobile|date=February 19, 2009|accessdate=November 22, 2009}}</ref> Also, during this time, four new play clocks and down/distance indicators were installed (one behind each corner of the end zones) and a new LED game clock was placed behind the south goalpost.\n\nThe expansion was completed in mid-summer [[2010 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2010]] and held an official capacity of 101,821 making it the fifth largest college football stadium in the country. The new seats were all sold out quickly for the entire 2010 football season. Subsequent expansions included stores and other extra amenities on the bottom of the end zone.\n\n===2020s renovations===\nAs part of a larger, 10-year $600 million plan to upgrade campus athletic facilities, the University is planning $92.5 million in upgrades to the stadium, including new social spaces, improved circulation, additional premium seating and upgraded spaces for athletes and recruits. The Walk of Champions will be extended into a new game day locker room via a new tunnel clad with video boards. The project will be funded with $48.4 million in bonds and $35 million from the Crimson Tide Foundation, the fundraising arm of UA athletics. Construction began shortly after the [[2019 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2019 season]].<ref>{{cite news|work=Tuscaloosa News|url=https://www.tuscaloosanews.com/news/20180921/bryant-denny-stadium-to-undergo-75-million-renovation|title=Bryant-Denny Stadium to undergo $75 million renovation|date=21 September 2018|accessdate=3 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=AL.com|url=https://www.al.com/alabamafootball/2019/06/big-changes-made-to-bryant-denny-stadium-renovation-plan.html|title=Big changes made to Bryant-Denny Stadium renovation plan|date=4 June 2019|accessdate=6 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nNew LED lights for the stadium were unveiled on the night of August 12, 2019, including a crimson-hued light display by the new installations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tuscaloosanews.com/news/20190813/bryant-denny-stadium-has-new-look|title=Bryant-Denny Stadium has new look|date=13 August 2019|accessdate=14 August 2019|work=Tuscaloosa News}}</ref>\n\n==Football lore==\n[[File:WalkofChampions 2010-11-26.jpg|thumb|left|The Walk of Champions prior to the 2010 [[Iron Bowl]]]]\nSince its opening in [[1929 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1929]] through [[2010 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2010]], the Crimson Tide owns a {{Winning percentage|212|50|3|record=y}} record at Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium.<ref name=\"BDS_all-time\">{{cite web |url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/alab/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/history-awards.pdf |title=Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium Year-By-Year Record |work=2010 Alabama Football Media Guide |publisher=University of Alabama Athletic Department |page=138 |accessdate=February 3, 2011 |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523102902/http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/alab/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/history-awards.pdf |archivedate=May 23, 2011 }}</ref> Bear Bryant is the leader in wins at the stadium, with an all-time record of {{Winning percentage|72|2|record=y}} in his quarter century as Tide head coach.<ref name=\"BDS_all-time\"/>\n\nDespite its success at Bryant\u2013Denny, most of Alabama's \"home\" football history from the 1920s through the 1980s occurred at Birmingham's Legion Field.<ref name=\"Legion_all-time\">{{cite web |title=2010 Alabama Football Media Guide|trans-title=Alabama Football at Legion Field|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/alab/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/history-awards.pdf|publisher=University of Alabama Department of Intercollegiate Athletics|accessdate=February 3, 2011|pages=141\u2013142|format=PDF|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523102902/http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/alab/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/history-awards.pdf|archivedate=May 23, 2011}}</ref> Well into the 1980s, Legion Field seated almost 20,000 more people than Bryant-Denny. As such, until the late 1990s, Legion Field hosted most of Alabama's important home games. The most notable of these games was the [[Iron Bowl]] with rival [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]]. Legion Field was considered a neutral site from 1948 through 1987. When the Iron Bowl became a home-and-home series in 1988, Alabama continued to host its home games in the series at Legion Field in even-numbered years through 1998. The Crimson Tide hosted Tennessee in odd-numbered years in Birmingham until 1999, and LSU in even-numbered years from 1964 through 1986, except for 1980. Usually, Bryant\u2013Denny hosted three or four games per season, mostly non-conference games, although the Tide always played Mississippi State in Tuscaloosa, save for 1987, due to the close distance between Tuscaloosa and [[Starkville, Mississippi|Starkville]]. However, in 1998, when Bryant\u2013Denny was expanded to a capacity exceeding Legion Field, the more important home games started to move to Bryant\u2013Denny, culminating with the move of the Tennessee series to Tuscaloosa in 1999 and the Iron Bowl a year later.<ref name=\"March 6, 1999\">{{cite news |title=Vols Due in Fall, AU in 2000|first=Cecil|last=Hurt|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=6ckdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VqYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6026%2C631746|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=March 6, 1999|accessdate=February 3, 2011|page=1}}</ref> From 1998 to 2003, Alabama continued to play two or three minor games in Birmingham. Finally, in 2003, Alabama played its final game at Legion Field against the [[South Florida Bulls]], and now Bryant\u2013Denny is the sole home of Alabama football.<ref name=\"Legion_all-time\"/>\n\n[[File:BDSfromDennyChimes.JPG|thumb|View of the northern side of the stadium and [[Tailgate party|tailgaters]] as seen from the [[Denny Chimes]] vicinity of [[University of Alabama Quad|The Quad]] in 2008.]]\nHowever, despite the majority of past big games being played at Legion Field, Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium has hosted many memorable games, such as the 1994 shootout between Alabama's [[Jay Barker]] and Georgia's [[Eric Zeier]], Marvin Constant's goal-line stop against [[1999 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]] quarterback Josh Booty as time expired in 1999, [[Tyrone Prothro]]'s reception over the back of Southern Miss defensive back Jasper Faulk in 2005, a 31\u20133 victory over No. 5 Florida in 2005, the [[Roman Harper]]-forced fumble against [[2005 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]] in 2005 that helped the Crimson Tide to victory, Alabama's 36\u20130 shutout victory against Auburn in 2008 thus breaking the six-game losing streak and first ever [[Iron Bowl]] victory in Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium, [[Terrence Cody]]'s field goal block against [[2009 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]] as time expired in 2009, and their 28-27 loss to the [[2010 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn Tigers]] known as the Camback where the Tide squandered a 24-0 lead against the Tigers. In recent years, Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium has become a feared place to play again.  Also Bryant-Denny has been put on many lists ranking it one of the best places to watch football. [[NCAA Football 11]] ranked Alabama's Bryant\u2013Denny as the fourth toughest place to play in the nation and third in the SEC behind [[Ben Hill Griffin Stadium|Florida]] and [[Tiger Stadium (LSU)|LSU]]. ''Sporting News'' ranks it first while Bleacher Report has it ranked as the 5th toughest and the 2nd best stadium in the country.<ref>{{cite web |title=College Football Rankings: 25 Best College Football Game Day Experiences|first=Wes|last=O'Donnell|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/592904-25-best-college-football-game-day-experiences/page/25|work=[[Bleacher Report]]|date=February 1, 2011|accessdate=September 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Field design==\n{{Panorama\n |image      = File:Bryant-Denny 10-22-11.jpg\n |fullwidth  = 7136\n |fullheight = 2392\n |caption    = The interior of Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium (south end zone, left) during a [[2011 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2011]] Alabama game versus [[2011 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]].\n |height     = 200\n}}\n\nUntil the turn of the millennium, the field at Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium had only the necessary markings required for play. As more and more stadiums began to add other designs to the field, such as logos, Alabama chose to remain traditional with the field design. In fact, even into the 2002 season, Bryant\u2013Denny still had no logo at midfield and no logos at the 25-yard lines, which are now commonplace in many stadiums. The end zone design simply consisted of \"ALABAMA\" in a white, block-style font. During the 1992 season, however, a special logo was used at midfield to commemorate the centennial season of Alabama football.\n\nDuring the 2002 season, however, a large white script \u201cA\u201d was added to midfield. The field design underwent full-scale changes beginning with the 2004 season. At midfield, the large white script \u201cA\u201d was replaced with the crimson script \u201cA\u201d logo, encircled by a crimson ring which has \"Alabama Crimson Tide\" written around it. In addition, the end zone designs were changed to a crimson block-style font outlined in white.\n\nFor the 2006 season, two identical logos commemorating the 175th anniversary of the university were also added to the field on the 25-yard lines. One was added on the south end of the stadium, on the west side of the playing field, while the other was on the north end of the stadium, on the east side of the playing field.\n\n[[File:2011 houndstooth ribbon on the field at Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium.jpg|thumb|right|alt=American football field with a houndstooth awareness ribbon painted on it.|left|Detail of the [[houndstooth]] [[awareness ribbon]] painted on-field in remembrance of the victims and damage of the April 2011 tornado.]]\nFor the 2007 season, two identical logos commemorating the 75th anniversary of the founding of the [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC) were added to home field of every SEC team. These were in the same places as the 175th logos were during the 2006 season.\n\nFor the 2008 season, two identical SEC logos were added to the home field of every SEC team. Alabama\u2019s crimson was used as the primary color for the logos at Bryant\u2013Denny. These logos were located in the same places as the previous logos and remain there today.\n\nFor the 2009 A-day game, the end zones were changed back to the original white block-style font that was used prior to the 2004 season, except that the background was shaded crimson. The north end zone displayed \"ALABAMA\", while the south end zone displayed \"CRIMSON TIDE\".  This design layout has remained in use since the 2009 season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Photo of Bryant-Denny Stadium Design for the 2009 A-day Game|url=http://i40.tinypic.com/dnp09e.jpg|publisher=Tiny Pic}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2011 season, two identical [[houndstooth]] [[awareness ribbon]]s recognizing the ongoing relief efforts following the [[2011 Tuscaloosa\u2013Birmingham tornado|April 27, 2011 tornado]] were added to the field on the 25 yard lines.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bryant\u2013Denny Unveils Tornado Ribbons|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/news?slug=rivals-1259179|work=[[Rivals.com|Rivals]]|date=September 1, 2011|accessdate=September 4, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Awareness\">{{cite news |title=Alabama's Opener Against Kent State Could Help Healing in Tuscaloosa|first=Izzy|last=Gould|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2011/09/alabamas_opener_against_kent_s.html|newspaper=[[Press-Register]]|location=Mobile|date=September 2, 2011|accessdate=March 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Locker rooms==\nIn 2008, the visitors' locker room was officially named \"The Fail Room\" after alumnus and donor [[James M. Fail]]. He commented, \"Earlier this year, when I saw the visitors' locker room as a potential naming right, I figured it was the most appropriate opportunity I would ever have to use my name.\"<ref>{{cite press release |title=Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium Visitors Locker Room Named for James M. Fail|url=http://www.rolltide.com/genrel/121508aab.html|publisher=University of Alabama Department of Intercollegiate Athletics|date=December 15, 2008|accessdate=December 15, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==High school championships==\nBeginning in 2009, Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium and [[Auburn University]]'s [[Jordan\u2013Hare Stadium]] became the homes of the [[Alabama High School Athletic Association]] state football championship games, known as the Super Seven. Bryant-Denny hosts the Super Seven in odd-numbered years, with Jordan\u2013Hare taking the games in even-numbered years. Previously, the Super Six was held at [[Legion Field]] in [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]].\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"150px\">\nBDS Night (Iron Bowl 2006).jpg|[[Iron Bowl]] [[2006 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2006]]\nBryant-Denny scoreboard.jpg|The old south end zone scoreboard in 2007. Installed in 1998, the JumboTron was removed during 2009-2010 renovations\nBryant Denny Stadium Walk of Champions.jpg|The Walk of Champions in 2008\nBDS West 2010-11-26.jpg|Looking west in [[2010 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2010]]\nBryant-Denny Stadium panoramic 2010-10-02.jpg|Panoramic view of interior, 2010\nStatues of Coaches at Bryant-Danny-Stadium.jpg|The \"Coaches Walk\" alongside the Walk of Champions in 2012. It features statues to prominent [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Crimson Tide football]] head coaches\nBryantDennyStadiumApril2013Tuscaloosa.png|Bryant-Denny Stadium in April 2013\nBryant Denny Stadium.jpg|Interior at night during off-season, 2015\nPresident Trump and First Lady Melania Trump in Alabama (49048699303).jpg|45th President of the United States [[Donald Trump]] at Bryant-Denny, November 2019\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.rolltide.com/sports/2016/6/10/facilities-bryant-denny-html.aspx Bryant-Denny Stadium page on Rolltide.com]\n\n{{Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{University of Alabama}}\n{{Southeastern Conference football venue navbox}}\n{{Alabama college football venues}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bryant-Denny Stadium}}\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football venues]]\n[[Category:American football venues in Alabama]]\n[[Category:College football venues]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Tuscaloosa, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1929]]\n[[Category:1929 establishments in Alabama]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1005:b156:99ec:40ec:46e0:173a:7608", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bryant%E2%80%93Denny_Stadium"}
{"title_page": "Haunted doll", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{refimprove|date=May 2017}}{{Unreliable sources|date=May 2019}}\n\nA '''haunted doll''' is a handmade or manufactured [[doll]] or [[stuffed animal]] that is reported to be cursed or [[Demonic possession|possessed]] in some way. The earliest report of a haunted doll goes back to [[Ancient Egypt]] where the enemies of [[Ramesses III]] attempted to use wax images of his likeness to bring about his death. The dolls used in this ritual were said to be living and would curse anyone who bore their resemblance. The ancient Egyptian poppet, effigy and voodoo dolls are often said to be cursed because of their long history of being used to place curses on other people and their association with the occult.If a doll is haunted,they will move without you moving it. Although most people do not believe in paranormal activity, it is very possible that it's real\n\n==Origins==\nThe earliest haunted dolls were [[poppet]]s, [[effigies]] and [[Haitian Vodou|voodoo]] objects which were created by early peoples for either religious or ceremonial purposes. These traditional objects were later acquired by various civilizations for mystical purposes or the occult.<ref name=\"paganwiccan.about.com\">{{cite web|url=http://paganwiccan.about.com/od/poppetmagic/p/Poppet_History.htm|title=Poppet History - Global Poppet Magic|author=Patti Wigington|work=About.com Religion & Spirituality}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=May 2019|certain=y}} In [[Ancient Rome|Rome]], dolls were used quite often in magical rituals to represent a connection with a god or goddess.<ref name=\"Magic In Greece and Rome\">{{cite web|url=https://www.academia.edu/3672405|title=An Examination of Ancient Greek and Roman Witches throughout Literature|author=Debbie Turkilsen|work=academia.edu}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=May 2019|certain=y}} Egyptian priests and magicians often used poppets for ceremonial purposes, to free the body of evil or to place curses on those who went against the will of the Gods.<ref name=\"Heka: Magic of Ancient Egypt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reshafim.org.il/ad/egypt/religion/magic.htm|title=Heka, the ancient Egyptian magic|work=reshafim.org.il|access-date=27 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131122111855/http://www.reshafim.org.il/ad/egypt/religion/magic.htm|archive-date=22 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=May 2019}}\n\nAccording to Wiccan beliefs, poppets have been used to place curses on members of a community, for religious, or traditional purposes.<ref name=\"paganwiccan.about.com\"/>{{Unreliable source?|date=May 2019|certain=y}} Some of the earliest effigies were used by African, Native American and European cultures. The European poppet has its roots in early Germanic and Scandinavian tribes who used them for ceremonial purposes.<ref name=\"paganwiccan.about.com\"/>{{Unreliable source?|date=May 2019|certain=y}} Modern day [[Wiccans]] have adapted this practice for their own uses. Most Wiccans believe a [[poppet]] is a symbolic representation of a person, and spells and other actions are performed on the poppet to transfer whatever might be affecting the targeted individual out of their body in something like a healing ritual.<ref name=\"paganwiccan.about.com\"/>{{Unreliable source?|date=May 2019|certain=y}} The Kongolese ''[[nkisi]]'' statuettes, and the ''bocio'' figurines used in Vodun traditions of Benin and Togo, are traditional [[effigy]]-like dolls of West and Central Africa believed by their practitioners to be \"spirit embodying\" forces that can also \"heal or protect\".<ref name=\"Bongmba2012\">{{cite book|author=Elias Kifon Bongmba|title=The Wiley-Blackwell Companion to African Religions|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JFRRl1vv0kwC&pg=PA118|date=21 May 2012|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-4051-9690-1|pages=118\u2013}}</ref> [[Voodoo doll]]s are fairly modern novelty items. Their concept is thought to be based on European poppet dolls.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n[[File:Lom\u00e9_Fetish_Market.jpg|thumb|[[Lom\u00e9]] Fetish Market]]\n\n=== West African Fetish Magic ===\n[[Fetishism]] is defined by ''[[Merriam-Webster]]'' as worshiping an object believed to have magical power to protect or aid its owner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/fetishes|title=Definition of FETISHES|website=Merriam-Webster|language=en|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref> In [[West Africa|West African]] culture, they used dolls placed inside or around homes, and for every wish or harm inflicted on another, a nail was driven into the doll's body.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://westafricandocumentary.com/power-and-magic|title=POWER AND MAGIC|website=WestAfricanDocumentary.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=May 2019|certain=y}} Additionally, chicken blood and other various liquids were often poured on the doll's body, and are described to have a malevolent ambience. Due to the alienness of African culture,{{According to whom|date=May 2019}} Europeans in the 16th and 17th centuries grew to be wary of these objects and believed they were evidence of [[Magic (supernatural)|sorcery]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=MacGaffey|first=Wyatt|date=1994|title=African Objects and the Idea of Fetish|journal=RES: Anthropology and Aesthetics|volume=25|issue=25|pages=123\u2013131|issn=0277-1322|jstor=20166895|doi=10.1086/RESv25n1ms20166895}}</ref>\n\n== Psychology ==\nResearch around why people perceive dolls as \"creepy\" has been conducted with some varying conclusions. A 2013 study by psychologist Frank McAndrew named doll collecting as one of the creepiest hobbies an individual could have. Of the topic of creepiness McAndrew stated that it was related to uncertainty, as something \"might be dangerous but you\u2019re not sure it is\".<ref name=\":0\" />{{Better source|date=May 2019|reason=Since this deals with psychology, a better source than the Smithsonian (arguably a popular press source) is needed.}} In a 2015 article for Smithsonian.com, writer Linda Rodriguez McRobbie stated that \"Dolls inhabit this area of uncertainty largely because they look human but we know they are not\".<ref name=\":0\" />{{Better source|date=May 2019|reason=Since this deals with psychology, a better source than the Smithsonian (arguably a popular press source) is needed.}} Since the doll lacks ability to mimic, human brains at the most basic evolutionary tactic remain suspicious of whether or not it is human since they may expect the doll to mimic their own actions. This leads to feelings of physical coldness when the doll does not act the way one thinks it should.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/history-creepy-dolls-180955916/|title=The History of Creepy Dolls|last=McRobbie|first=Linda Rodriguez|website=Smithsonian|language=en|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref>{{Better source|date=May 2019|reason=Since this deals with psychology, a better source than the Smithsonian (arguably a popular press source) is needed.}} \n\n== The market ==\nAs of 2017, a market has arisen where consumers search for dolls that come with supposed paranormal phenomena. Movies about certain dolls, like [[Annabelle (doll)|Annabelle]], have created a desire to explore claims of haunted dolls. According to Katherine Carlson of ''[[The New Yorker]]'', such dolls bring with them a certain fascination that a regular doll does not, since \"a haunted doll requires proof \u2014 or at least enough of a backstory that a prospective buyer can embrace the possibility of the supernatural\".<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/rabbit-holes/ebay-fantastical-earnest-world-haunted-dolls|title=On eBay, a Fantastical, Earnest World of Haunted Dolls|last=Carlson|first=Katherine|date=2017-10-31|access-date=2019-04-10|work=The New Yorker}}</ref> The dolls are typically sold by private users and can be found for sale on [[eBay]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[Etsy]] and many other sites. Carlson reports that sales listings are often accompanied by stories and claims detailing the background of the doll and claimed paranormal phenomena.<ref name=\":02\" /> Folklore professor Libby Tucker purchased an allegedly haunted doll for discussion in her ''Folklore of the Supernatural'' class, and said that the value of such items for folklore researchers is considerable.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Tucker|first=Libby|date=Fall 2009|title=Tiny Feet on the Stairs|url=https://search.proquest.com/openview/988e34e0c41436bee521db57df9b7bb3/1?pq-origsite=gscholar&cbl=26490|journal=Schenectady|volume=35|issue=3/4|pages=22|via=ProQuest}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Chucky the doll.jpg|thumb|264x264px|Chucky the doll from the movie ''Child's Play'' ]]\n\n== Haunted dolls in pop culture ==\n\n=== Haunted dolls in movies ===\nDolls like Robert and Annabelle have been inspirations to movies. ''[[Child's Play (1988 film)|Child's Play]],'' a movie produced and released in 1988, follows a killer doll named [[Chucky (character)|Chucky]], and was inspired by the story of [[Robert (doll)|Robert The Doll]]. The popularity of the first movie led way to ''[[Child's Play 2|Child's play 2]],'' and ''[[Child's Play 3]].'' Being a hit, Chucky made its way into pop culture, being referenced in''[[The Simpsons]],'' and ''[[Saturday Night Live]].'' The whole franchise grossed in more than 250 million U.S dollars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2013/10/08/curse-of-chucky-25-years/2861753/|title=After 25 years, Chucky is both a blessing and a 'Curse'|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref> The doll Annabelle was the source of inspiration in the ''[[Annabelle (film)|Annabelle]]'' series and the doll featured in ''[[The Conjuring]].''{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}} \n\n=== Haunted dolls on TV ===\n\nHaunted dolls have also made appearances in TV. In an episode of ''[[Ghost Hunters (TV series)|Ghost Hunters]]'' they visit a haunted Island of dolls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.travelchannel.com/shows/ghost-adventures/articles/qanda-zak-bagans-on-the-island-of-the-dolls|title=Q&A: Zak Bagans on the Island of the Dolls|website=Travel Channel|language=en|access-date=2019-03-29}}</ref> Additionally, a murdering haunted doll named \"Talky Tina,\" appeared in ''The Twilight Zone.'' The doll was inspired by the real life toy \"Chatty Cathy.\" This episode became inspiration to [[The Simpsons|''The'' ''Simpsons'']] in a \"[[Treehouse of Horror|Tree house of horror episode]].\" However, instead of it being \"Talky Tina,\" it was a [[Krusty the Clown]] doll toy.<ref>{{Citation|last=eman4240|title=Evil Krusty|date=2011-10-22|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4vTCzi8WY3Y|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref> In the ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants|SpongeBob Squarepants]]'' episode \"Sanitation Insanity,\" [[Squidward Tentacles|Squidward]] and SpongeBob find a talking doll. The doll goes on to say that it wants to destroy Squidward.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bubbleblabber.com/review-spongebob-squarepants-sanitation-insanity/|title=Review: SpongeBob SquarePants- \"Sanitation Insanity\"|last=King|first=David|date=2018-05-08|website=Bubbleblabber|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Haunted dolls in other forms of media ===\n\n\nA recurring bit on the [[podcast]] [[My Brother, My Brother and Me]] is \"haunted doll watch\", a segment where the brothers read descriptions of allegedly haunted dolls for sale on [[eBay]].\n\n==Famous haunted dolls==\nAlthough tales of haunted dolls or cursed objects in general have a long history, a number of supposedly haunted dolls have appeared in [[popular culture]] in recent years.<ref name=\"PulliamFonseca2016\">{{cite book|author1=June Pulliam|author2=Anthony Fonseca|title=Ghosts in Popular Culture and Legend|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RUfpDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA83|date=26 September 2016|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-4408-3491-2|pages=83\u2013}}</ref>\n\n===Robert===\n[[Image:Robert The Doll (5999680656).jpg|thumb|Robert the doll]]\n{{main article|Robert (doll)}}\nRobert is a doll on display at the [[East Martello Museum]] in Key West, Florida that was once owned by [[Key West]] painter and author Robert Eugene Otto.  The doll is alleged to be possessed by spirits,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northjersey.com/travel/schensul-if-you-go-to-key-west-fla-beware-of-robert-the-doll-1.670857?page=all|title=Schensul: If you go to Key West, Fla., beware of Robert the Doll|author=Schensul, Jill|publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=12 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/atlas_obscura/2013/11/18/robert_the_haunted_doll_creeping_out_floridians_since_1904.html|title=Robert the Haunted Doll: Creeping Out Floridians Since 1904|author=Ella Morton|publisher=Slate.com|date=18 November 2013}}</ref> and was the inspiration for [[Chucky (Child's Play)|Chucky]], the doll in the 1988 horror film ''[[Child's Play (1988 film)|Child's Play]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ihorror.com/meet-robert-creepy-doll-inspired-childs-play/|title=Meet Robert; The Haunted Doll That Inspired Child's Play|author=Squires, John|publisher=iHorror|date=29 January 2014|accessdate=3 December 2014}}</ref> \n\n===Annabelle===\n{{main article|Annabelle (doll)}}\nAnnabelle is a [[Raggedy Ann]] doll alleged by [[Ed and Lorraine Warren]] to be haunted<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aol.com/article/2014/10/28/the-story-behind-the-evil-and-dangerous-annabelle-doll/20985407/|title=The story behind the 'evil' and 'dangerous' Annabelle doll|author=Nancy Lynch|publisher=[[AOL]]|date=28 October 2014}}</ref> and displayed in The Warren's Occult Museum in [[Monroe, Connecticut]]. The doll served as the inspiration for the films ''[[The Conjuring]]'' and ''[[Annabelle (film)|Annabelle]]''.<ref name=IBT>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/annabelle-true-story-9-freaky-facts-about-real-doll-haunting-ahead-movie-release-1698694|title='Annabelle' True Story: 9 Freaky Facts About The Real Doll Haunting Ahead Of Movie Release|author=Rebecka Schumann|publisher=[[International Business Times]]|date=2 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Letta the Doll===\nKerry Walton, of Brisbane, Australia has appeared on a number of television programs with a doll he claims to have found while visiting an abandoned building in 1972 in \n[[Wagga Wagga|Wagga Wagga, Australia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thechronicle.com.au/news/mystery-behind-200-year-old-doll-from-hell/3098881/|title=Mystery surrounds 200-year-old 'haunted doll from hell'|last=Harris|first=Meghan|website=Chronicle|language=en|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref> According to Walton, he named the doll \"Letta Me Out\" because of its supposedly supernatural characteristics.<ref name=\"freakydolls.listverse.com\"/> Kerry claims to have experienced the first supernatural occurrence when his children reported seeing objects moving around their house at night, and that people have seen the doll move in front of them and that the doll has left visible scuff marks around the house. Currently, Letta Me Out is owned by Kerry in [[Warwick, Queensland]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/entertainment/letta-me-out-cursed-australian-doll/|title=Meet 'Letta Me Out', An Extremely Haunted 200 Year Old Doll From Wagga|date=2018-09-07|website=Pedestrian TV|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-30}}</ref>\n\n=== Okiku ===\nAccording to modern Japanese folklore, in 1918, a teenager named Eikichi Suzuki purchased a large doll from [[Hokkaido]] for his younger sister, Okiku, who gave the doll her name. When Okiku died, her family came to believe that Okiku's spirit was inhabiting the doll and the hair on the doll was growing. The doll resides in [[Mannenji Temple]] in Hokkaido, where it is claimed that a priest regularly trims Okiku's still-growing hair.<ref name=\"Ross2011\">{{cite book|author=Catrien Ross|title=Japanese Ghost Stories: Spirits, Hauntings, and Paranormal Phenomena|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yYLQAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT82|date=30 August 2011|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|isbn=978-1-4629-0100-5|pages=82\u2013}}</ref>\n\n===Pupa===\nAccording to stories published on the internet, Pupa is a doll said to \"contain the spirit\" of a dead Italian girl.<ref name=\"freakydolls.listverse.com\"/> \n\n===Mandy===\nMade in England or Germany between 1910 and 1920, Mandy is a porcelain baby doll donated to the Quesnel Museum in British Columbia in 1991. Mandy is also said to have supernatural powers.<ref name=\"freakydolls.listverse.com\"/>  Mandy sits in a case with a toy lamb on her lap and museum visitors have reported seeing the lamb outside of the case. Other visitors claim that Mandy's eyes follow them as they walk in the room. The doll gained notoriety when it appeared alongside the curator and donor of the doll on the [[The Montel Williams Show|Montel Williams Show.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2018/10/31/haunted-doll-canada_a_23577068/|title=Canada Is Home To One Of The World's Most Famous Haunted Dolls|date=2018-10-31|website=HuffPost Canada|language=en|access-date=2019-03-30}}</ref>\n\n===Pulau Ubin Barbie===\nAccording to Singapore legend, Pulau Ubin Barbie is a [[Barbie doll]] displayed in a memorial temple said to have supernatural powers.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Worshippers offer cosmetics to Barbie doll at Pulau Ubin temple|url = http://news.asiaone.com/News/Latest%252BNews/Singapore/Story/A1Story20130329-412295.html|website = AsiaOne|accessdate = 23 November 2015|publisher = Singapore Press Holdings|date = 29 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"freakydolls.listverse.com\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Killer toy]]\n*[[Voodoo doll]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2|refs=\n<ref name=\"freakydolls.listverse.com\">{{cite web|url=http://listverse.com/2014/04/04/10-freaky-dolls-you-dont-want-to-play-with/|title=10 Freaky Dolls You Don't Want To Play With|work=Listverse}}{{unreliable source?|date=March 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.academia.edu/3672405/An_Examination_of_Ancient_Greek_and_Roman_Witches_throughout_Literature An Examination of Ancient Greek and Roman Witches throughout Literature]\n*[http://academics.smcvt.edu/africanart2/Thomas/Vodou/origins2.htm History of Bocio Dolls]\n\n[[Category:Curses]]\n[[Category:Dolls]]\n[[Category:Urban legends]]\n[[Category:Supernatural]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{refimprove|date=May 2017}}{{Unreliable sources|date=May 2019}}\n\nA '''haunted doll''' is a handmade or manufactured [[doll]] or [[stuffed animal]] that is reported to be cursed or [[Demonic possession|possessed]] in some way. The earliest report of a haunted doll goes back to [[Ancient Egypt]] where the enemies of [[Ramesses III]] attempted to use wax images of his likeness to bring about his death. The dolls used in this ritual were said to be living and would curse anyone who bore their resemblance. The ancient Egyptian poppet, effigy and voodoo dolls are often said to be cursed because of their long history of being used to place curses on other people and their association with the occult.\n\n==Origins==\nThe earliest haunted dolls were [[poppet]]s, [[effigies]] and [[Haitian Vodou|voodoo]] objects which were created by early peoples for either religious or ceremonial purposes. These traditional objects were later acquired by various civilizations for mystical purposes or the occult.<ref name=\"paganwiccan.about.com\">{{cite web|url=http://paganwiccan.about.com/od/poppetmagic/p/Poppet_History.htm|title=Poppet History - Global Poppet Magic|author=Patti Wigington|work=About.com Religion & Spirituality}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=May 2019|certain=y}} In [[Ancient Rome|Rome]], dolls were used quite often in magical rituals to represent a connection with a god or goddess.<ref name=\"Magic In Greece and Rome\">{{cite web|url=https://www.academia.edu/3672405|title=An Examination of Ancient Greek and Roman Witches throughout Literature|author=Debbie Turkilsen|work=academia.edu}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=May 2019|certain=y}} Egyptian priests and magicians often used poppets for ceremonial purposes, to free the body of evil or to place curses on those who went against the will of the Gods.<ref name=\"Heka: Magic of Ancient Egypt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reshafim.org.il/ad/egypt/religion/magic.htm|title=Heka, the ancient Egyptian magic|work=reshafim.org.il|access-date=27 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131122111855/http://www.reshafim.org.il/ad/egypt/religion/magic.htm|archive-date=22 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=May 2019}}\n\nAccording to Wiccan beliefs, poppets have been used to place curses on members of a community, for religious, or traditional purposes.<ref name=\"paganwiccan.about.com\"/>{{Unreliable source?|date=May 2019|certain=y}} Some of the earliest effigies were used by African, Native American and European cultures. The European poppet has its roots in early Germanic and Scandinavian tribes who used them for ceremonial purposes.<ref name=\"paganwiccan.about.com\"/>{{Unreliable source?|date=May 2019|certain=y}} Modern day [[Wiccans]] have adapted this practice for their own uses. Most Wiccans believe a [[poppet]] is a symbolic representation of a person, and spells and other actions are performed on the poppet to transfer whatever might be affecting the targeted individual out of their body in something like a healing ritual.<ref name=\"paganwiccan.about.com\"/>{{Unreliable source?|date=May 2019|certain=y}} The Kongolese ''[[nkisi]]'' statuettes, and the ''bocio'' figurines used in Vodun traditions of Benin and Togo, are traditional [[effigy]]-like dolls of West and Central Africa believed by their practitioners to be \"spirit embodying\" forces that can also \"heal or protect\".<ref name=\"Bongmba2012\">{{cite book|author=Elias Kifon Bongmba|title=The Wiley-Blackwell Companion to African Religions|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JFRRl1vv0kwC&pg=PA118|date=21 May 2012|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-4051-9690-1|pages=118\u2013}}</ref> [[Voodoo doll]]s are fairly modern novelty items. Their concept is thought to be based on European poppet dolls.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n[[File:Lom\u00e9_Fetish_Market.jpg|thumb|[[Lom\u00e9]] Fetish Market]]\n\n=== West African Fetish Magic ===\n[[Fetishism]] is defined by ''[[Merriam-Webster]]'' as worshiping an object believed to have magical power to protect or aid its owner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/fetishes|title=Definition of FETISHES|website=Merriam-Webster|language=en|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref> In [[West Africa|West African]] culture, they used dolls placed inside or around homes, and for every wish or harm inflicted on another, a nail was driven into the doll's body.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://westafricandocumentary.com/power-and-magic|title=POWER AND MAGIC|website=WestAfricanDocumentary.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=May 2019|certain=y}} Additionally, chicken blood and other various liquids were often poured on the doll's body, and are described to have a malevolent ambience. Due to the alienness of African culture,{{According to whom|date=May 2019}} Europeans in the 16th and 17th centuries grew to be wary of these objects and believed they were evidence of [[Magic (supernatural)|sorcery]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=MacGaffey|first=Wyatt|date=1994|title=African Objects and the Idea of Fetish|journal=RES: Anthropology and Aesthetics|volume=25|issue=25|pages=123\u2013131|issn=0277-1322|jstor=20166895|doi=10.1086/RESv25n1ms20166895}}</ref>\n\n== Psychology ==\nResearch around why people perceive dolls as \"creepy\" has been conducted with some varying conclusions. A 2013 study by psychologist Frank McAndrew named doll collecting as one of the creepiest hobbies an individual could have. Of the topic of creepiness McAndrew stated that it was related to uncertainty, as something \"might be dangerous but you\u2019re not sure it is\".<ref name=\":0\" />{{Better source|date=May 2019|reason=Since this deals with psychology, a better source than the Smithsonian (arguably a popular press source) is needed.}} In a 2015 article for Smithsonian.com, writer Linda Rodriguez McRobbie stated that \"Dolls inhabit this area of uncertainty largely because they look human but we know they are not\".<ref name=\":0\" />{{Better source|date=May 2019|reason=Since this deals with psychology, a better source than the Smithsonian (arguably a popular press source) is needed.}} Since the doll lacks ability to mimic, human brains at the most basic evolutionary tactic remain suspicious of whether or not it is human since they may expect the doll to mimic their own actions. This leads to feelings of physical coldness when the doll does not act the way one thinks it should.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/history-creepy-dolls-180955916/|title=The History of Creepy Dolls|last=McRobbie|first=Linda Rodriguez|website=Smithsonian|language=en|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref>{{Better source|date=May 2019|reason=Since this deals with psychology, a better source than the Smithsonian (arguably a popular press source) is needed.}} \n\n== The market ==\nAs of 2017, a market has arisen where consumers search for dolls that come with supposed paranormal phenomena. Movies about certain dolls, like [[Annabelle (doll)|Annabelle]], have created a desire to explore claims of haunted dolls. According to Katherine Carlson of ''[[The New Yorker]]'', such dolls bring with them a certain fascination that a regular doll does not, since \"a haunted doll requires proof \u2014 or at least enough of a backstory that a prospective buyer can embrace the possibility of the supernatural\".<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/rabbit-holes/ebay-fantastical-earnest-world-haunted-dolls|title=On eBay, a Fantastical, Earnest World of Haunted Dolls|last=Carlson|first=Katherine|date=2017-10-31|access-date=2019-04-10|work=The New Yorker}}</ref> The dolls are typically sold by private users and can be found for sale on [[eBay]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[Etsy]] and many other sites. Carlson reports that sales listings are often accompanied by stories and claims detailing the background of the doll and claimed paranormal phenomena.<ref name=\":02\" /> Folklore professor Libby Tucker purchased an allegedly haunted doll for discussion in her ''Folklore of the Supernatural'' class, and said that the value of such items for folklore researchers is considerable.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Tucker|first=Libby|date=Fall 2009|title=Tiny Feet on the Stairs|url=https://search.proquest.com/openview/988e34e0c41436bee521db57df9b7bb3/1?pq-origsite=gscholar&cbl=26490|journal=Schenectady|volume=35|issue=3/4|pages=22|via=ProQuest}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Chucky the doll.jpg|thumb|264x264px|Chucky the doll from the movie ''Child's Play'' ]]\n\n== Haunted dolls in pop culture ==\n\n=== Haunted dolls in movies ===\nDolls like Robert and Annabelle have been inspirations to movies. ''[[Child's Play (1988 film)|Child's Play]],'' a movie produced and released in 1988, follows a killer doll named [[Chucky (character)|Chucky]], and was inspired by the story of [[Robert (doll)|Robert The Doll]]. The popularity of the first movie led way to ''[[Child's Play 2|Child's play 2]],'' and ''[[Child's Play 3]].'' Being a hit, Chucky made its way into pop culture, being referenced in''[[The Simpsons]],'' and ''[[Saturday Night Live]].'' The whole franchise grossed in more than 250 million U.S dollars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2013/10/08/curse-of-chucky-25-years/2861753/|title=After 25 years, Chucky is both a blessing and a 'Curse'|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref> The doll Annabelle was the source of inspiration in the ''[[Annabelle (film)|Annabelle]]'' series and the doll featured in ''[[The Conjuring]].''{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}} \n\n=== Haunted dolls on TV ===\n\nHaunted dolls have also made appearances in TV. In an episode of ''[[Ghost Hunters (TV series)|Ghost Hunters]]'' they visit a haunted Island of dolls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.travelchannel.com/shows/ghost-adventures/articles/qanda-zak-bagans-on-the-island-of-the-dolls|title=Q&A: Zak Bagans on the Island of the Dolls|website=Travel Channel|language=en|access-date=2019-03-29}}</ref> Additionally, a murdering haunted doll named \"Talky Tina,\" appeared in ''The Twilight Zone.'' The doll was inspired by the real life toy \"Chatty Cathy.\" This episode became inspiration to [[The Simpsons|''The'' ''Simpsons'']] in a \"[[Treehouse of Horror|Tree house of horror episode]].\" However, instead of it being \"Talky Tina,\" it was a [[Krusty the Clown]] doll toy.<ref>{{Citation|last=eman4240|title=Evil Krusty|date=2011-10-22|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4vTCzi8WY3Y|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref> In the ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants|SpongeBob Squarepants]]'' episode \"Sanitation Insanity,\" [[Squidward Tentacles|Squidward]] and SpongeBob find a talking doll. The doll goes on to say that it wants to destroy Squidward.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bubbleblabber.com/review-spongebob-squarepants-sanitation-insanity/|title=Review: SpongeBob SquarePants- \"Sanitation Insanity\"|last=King|first=David|date=2018-05-08|website=Bubbleblabber|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Haunted dolls in other forms of media ===\n\n\nA recurring bit on the [[podcast]] [[My Brother, My Brother and Me]] is \"haunted doll watch\", a segment where the brothers read descriptions of allegedly haunted dolls for sale on [[eBay]].\n\n==Famous haunted dolls==\nAlthough tales of haunted dolls or cursed objects in general have a long history, a number of supposedly haunted dolls have appeared in [[popular culture]] in recent years.<ref name=\"PulliamFonseca2016\">{{cite book|author1=June Pulliam|author2=Anthony Fonseca|title=Ghosts in Popular Culture and Legend|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RUfpDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA83|date=26 September 2016|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-4408-3491-2|pages=83\u2013}}</ref>\n\n===Robert===\n[[Image:Robert The Doll (5999680656).jpg|thumb|Robert the doll]]\n{{main article|Robert (doll)}}\nRobert is a doll on display at the [[East Martello Museum]] in Key West, Florida that was once owned by [[Key West]] painter and author Robert Eugene Otto.  The doll is alleged to be possessed by spirits,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northjersey.com/travel/schensul-if-you-go-to-key-west-fla-beware-of-robert-the-doll-1.670857?page=all|title=Schensul: If you go to Key West, Fla., beware of Robert the Doll|author=Schensul, Jill|publisher=NorthJersey.com|date=12 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/atlas_obscura/2013/11/18/robert_the_haunted_doll_creeping_out_floridians_since_1904.html|title=Robert the Haunted Doll: Creeping Out Floridians Since 1904|author=Ella Morton|publisher=Slate.com|date=18 November 2013}}</ref> and was the inspiration for [[Chucky (Child's Play)|Chucky]], the doll in the 1988 horror film ''[[Child's Play (1988 film)|Child's Play]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ihorror.com/meet-robert-creepy-doll-inspired-childs-play/|title=Meet Robert; The Haunted Doll That Inspired Child's Play|author=Squires, John|publisher=iHorror|date=29 January 2014|accessdate=3 December 2014}}</ref> \n\n===Annabelle===\n{{main article|Annabelle (doll)}}\nAnnabelle is a [[Raggedy Ann]] doll alleged by [[Ed and Lorraine Warren]] to be haunted<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aol.com/article/2014/10/28/the-story-behind-the-evil-and-dangerous-annabelle-doll/20985407/|title=The story behind the 'evil' and 'dangerous' Annabelle doll|author=Nancy Lynch|publisher=[[AOL]]|date=28 October 2014}}</ref> and displayed in The Warren's Occult Museum in [[Monroe, Connecticut]]. The doll served as the inspiration for the films ''[[The Conjuring]]'' and ''[[Annabelle (film)|Annabelle]]''.<ref name=IBT>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/annabelle-true-story-9-freaky-facts-about-real-doll-haunting-ahead-movie-release-1698694|title='Annabelle' True Story: 9 Freaky Facts About The Real Doll Haunting Ahead Of Movie Release|author=Rebecka Schumann|publisher=[[International Business Times]]|date=2 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Letta the Doll===\nKerry Walton, of Brisbane, Australia has appeared on a number of television programs with a doll he claims to have found while visiting an abandoned building in 1972 in \n[[Wagga Wagga|Wagga Wagga, Australia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thechronicle.com.au/news/mystery-behind-200-year-old-doll-from-hell/3098881/|title=Mystery surrounds 200-year-old 'haunted doll from hell'|last=Harris|first=Meghan|website=Chronicle|language=en|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref> According to Walton, he named the doll \"Letta Me Out\" because of its supposedly supernatural characteristics.<ref name=\"freakydolls.listverse.com\"/> Kerry claims to have experienced the first supernatural occurrence when his children reported seeing objects moving around their house at night, and that people have seen the doll move in front of them and that the doll has left visible scuff marks around the house. Currently, Letta Me Out is owned by Kerry in [[Warwick, Queensland]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/entertainment/letta-me-out-cursed-australian-doll/|title=Meet 'Letta Me Out', An Extremely Haunted 200 Year Old Doll From Wagga|date=2018-09-07|website=Pedestrian TV|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-30}}</ref>\n\n=== Okiku ===\nAccording to modern Japanese folklore, in 1918, a teenager named Eikichi Suzuki purchased a large doll from [[Hokkaido]] for his younger sister, Okiku, who gave the doll her name. When Okiku died, her family came to believe that Okiku's spirit was inhabiting the doll and the hair on the doll was growing. The doll resides in [[Mannenji Temple]] in Hokkaido, where it is claimed that a priest regularly trims Okiku's still-growing hair.<ref name=\"Ross2011\">{{cite book|author=Catrien Ross|title=Japanese Ghost Stories: Spirits, Hauntings, and Paranormal Phenomena|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yYLQAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT82|date=30 August 2011|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|isbn=978-1-4629-0100-5|pages=82\u2013}}</ref>\n\n===Pupa===\nAccording to stories published on the internet, Pupa is a doll said to \"contain the spirit\" of a dead Italian girl.<ref name=\"freakydolls.listverse.com\"/> \n\n===Mandy===\nMade in England or Germany between 1910 and 1920, Mandy is a porcelain baby doll donated to the Quesnel Museum in British Columbia in 1991. Mandy is also said to have supernatural powers.<ref name=\"freakydolls.listverse.com\"/>  Mandy sits in a case with a toy lamb on her lap and museum visitors have reported seeing the lamb outside of the case. Other visitors claim that Mandy's eyes follow them as they walk in the room. The doll gained notoriety when it appeared alongside the curator and donor of the doll on the [[The Montel Williams Show|Montel Williams Show.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2018/10/31/haunted-doll-canada_a_23577068/|title=Canada Is Home To One Of The World's Most Famous Haunted Dolls|date=2018-10-31|website=HuffPost Canada|language=en|access-date=2019-03-30}}</ref>\n\n===Pulau Ubin Barbie===\nAccording to Singapore legend, Pulau Ubin Barbie is a [[Barbie doll]] displayed in a memorial temple said to have supernatural powers.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Worshippers offer cosmetics to Barbie doll at Pulau Ubin temple|url = http://news.asiaone.com/News/Latest%252BNews/Singapore/Story/A1Story20130329-412295.html|website = AsiaOne|accessdate = 23 November 2015|publisher = Singapore Press Holdings|date = 29 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"freakydolls.listverse.com\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Killer toy]]\n*[[Voodoo doll]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2|refs=\n<ref name=\"freakydolls.listverse.com\">{{cite web|url=http://listverse.com/2014/04/04/10-freaky-dolls-you-dont-want-to-play-with/|title=10 Freaky Dolls You Don't Want To Play With|work=Listverse}}{{unreliable source?|date=March 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.academia.edu/3672405/An_Examination_of_Ancient_Greek_and_Roman_Witches_throughout_Literature An Examination of Ancient Greek and Roman Witches throughout Literature]\n*[http://academics.smcvt.edu/africanart2/Thomas/Vodou/origins2.htm History of Bocio Dolls]\n\n[[Category:Curses]]\n[[Category:Dolls]]\n[[Category:Urban legends]]\n[[Category:Supernatural]]\n", "name_user": "2600:387:0:9a2::34", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haunted_doll"}
{"title_page": "Saul Bass", "text_new": "{{pp-move-indef|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American graphic designer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Saul Bass\n| image = Saul Bass.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1920|5|8}}\n| birth_place = [[The Bronx]], New York, U.S.\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1996|4|25|1920|5|8}}\n| death_place = [[Los Angeles]], California, U.S.\n| nationality = American\n| known_for = \n| occupation = [[Graphic designer]], title designer, film director\n| awards = {{ubl|Academy Award, Best Documentary, Short Subjects, ''Why Man Creates'' (1968)|Honorary Doctorate, [[Otis College of Art and Design]](1986)}}\n|spouse= {{ubl|Ruth Cooper (1938\u20131960)|[[Elaine Makatura Bass]] (1961\u20131996; his death)}}\n| children = 4\n}}\n\n'''Saul Bass''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u00e6|s}}; May 8, 1920&nbsp;\u2013 April 25, 1996) was an American [[graphic designer]] and [[Academy Awards|Oscar]]-winning filmmaker, best known for his design of motion-picture [[title sequence]]s, [[film poster]]s, and [[logo|corporate logos]].\n\nDuring his 40-year career, Bass worked for some of Hollywood's most prominent filmmakers, including [[Alfred Hitchcock]], [[Otto Preminger]], [[Billy Wilder]], [[Stanley Kubrick]] and [[Martin Scorsese]]. Among his most famous [[title sequence]]s are the animated paper cut-out of a heroin addict's arm for Preminger's ''[[The Man with the Golden Arm]]'', the credits racing up and down what eventually becomes a high-angle shot of a skyscraper in Hitchcock's ''[[North by Northwest]]'', and the disjointed text that races together and apart in ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]''.\n\nBass designed some of the most iconic corporate logos in North America, including the [[Bell System]] logo in 1969, as well as [[American Telephone & Telegraph Company|AT&T]]'s globe logo in 1983 after the [[Bell System divestiture|breakup of the Bell System]]. He also designed [[Continental Airlines]]' 1968 jet stream logo and [[United Airlines]]' 1974 tulip logo, which became some of the most recognized airline industry logos of the era. He died from [[non-Hodgkin's lymphoma]] in Los Angeles on April 25, 1996, at the age of 75.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1996-04-27-9604260612-story.html|title=SAUL BASS, 75, LOGO AND TRADEMARK DESIGNER|first=Los Angeles|last=Times|website=Sun-Sentinel.com}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSaul Bass was born on May 8, 1920 in [[the Bronx]], New York, United States, to Eastern European Jewish immigrant parents. He graduated from [[James Monroe High School (New York)|James Monroe High School]] in [[the Bronx]] and studied part-time at the [[Art Students League of New York|Art Students League]] in Manhattan until attending night classes with [[Gy\u00f6rgy Kepes]] at [[Brooklyn College]].<ref name=\"kirkham2011\">{{cite journal|last=Kirkham|first=Pat|title=Reassessing the Saul Bass and Alfred Hitchcock Collaboration|date=10 February 2011|volume=18|url=http://www.west86th.bgc.bard.edu/articles/kirkham-bass-hitchcock.html|journal=West 86th}}</ref> In 1938, Saul married Ruth Cooper and they had two children, Robert in 1942 and Andrea in 1946.<ref name=\"horak\">{{cite book|last1=Horak|first1=Jan-Christopher|title=Saul Bass: Anatomy of Film Design|date=2014|publisher=The University of Kentucky Press|isbn=0813147190}}</ref>\n\nHe began his time in Hollywood in the 1940s, designing print advertisements for films including ''[[Champion (1949 film)|Champion]]'' (1949), ''[[Death of a Salesman (1951 film)|Death of a Salesman]]'' (1951) and ''[[The Moon Is Blue]]'' (1953), directed by Otto Preminger. His next collaboration with Preminger was to design a [[film poster]] for his 1954 film ''[[Carmen Jones (film)|Carmen Jones]]''. Preminger was so impressed with Bass's work that he asked him to produce the title sequence as well. This was when Bass first saw the opportunity to create a title sequence which would ultimately enhance the experience of the audience and contribute to the mood and the theme of the movie within the opening moments. Bass was one of the first to realize the creative potential of the opening and closing credits of a movie.\n\n==Film title sequences==\n\n\n\nIn 1955, [[Elaine Makatura Bass|Elaine Makatura]] came to work with Bass in his Los Angeles office. By 1960, with the opening to ''[[Spartacus (film)|Spartacus]]'', she was directing and producing title sequences, and in 1961 the two married, beginning more than 40 years of close collaboration. After the birth of their children, Jennifer in 1964 and Jeffrey in 1967, they concentrated on their family, film directing, and title sequences. Saul and Elaine designed title sequences for more than 40 years, continuously experimenting with a variety of innovative techniques and effects, from [[Bunraku]]-style maneuvers in ''[[Spartacus]]'' (1960), live-action sequences in ''[[Walk on the Wild Side (film)|Walk On The Wild Side]]'' (1962), to time-lapse photography in ''[[The Age of Innocence]]'' (1993), and even chopped liver in ''[[Mr. Saturday Night]]'' (1992). Their live-action opening title sequences often served as prologues to their films and transitioned seamlessly into their opening scenes. These \"time before\" title sequences either compress or expand time with startling results. The title sequence to ''[[Grand Prix (1966 film)|Grand Prix]]'' (1966) portrays the moments before the opening race in Monte Carlo, the title sequence to ''[[The Big Country]]'' (1958) depicts the days it takes a stage coach to travel to a remote Western town, and the opening montage title sequence to ''[[The Victors (film)|The Victors]]'' (1963) chronicles the twenty-seven years between World War I and the middle of World War II, where the film begins.\n\nFrom the mid-1960s to the late '80s, Saul and Elaine moved away from main titles to focus on filmmaking and their children. About this time away from title design, Saul said:<ref>{{cite web|title=Saul Bass|url=http://www.artofthetitle.com/designer/saul-bass/|website=Art of the Title|accessdate=13 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Elaine and I feel we are there to serve the film and to approach the task with a sense of responsibility. We saw a lot of pyrotechnics and fun and games and I suppose we lost interest. At the same time, an increasing number of directors now sought to open their own films in ambitious ways rather than hire someone else to do it. Whatever the reasons, the result was \"Fade Out.\" We did not worry about it: we had too many other interesting projects to get on with. Equally, because we still loved the process of making titles, we were happy to take it up again when asked. \"Fade In\"...<ref>Jennifer Bass and Pat Kirkham, ''Saul Bass: A Life in Film & Design'', Laurence King Publishing, 2011, p. 264</ref>}}\n\nIn the 1980s, Saul and Elaine were rediscovered by [[James L. Brooks]] and [[Martin Scorsese]], who had grown up admiring their film work.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/filmtvinfo/library/eventsexh/past/saulbass/biography.html |title=Library &#124; Exhibitions and Events &#124; Saul Bass: biography |publisher=BFI |date=2012-05-11 |accessdate=2012-06-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706073216/http://www.bfi.org.uk/filmtvinfo/library/eventsexh/past/saulbass/biography.html |archivedate=2011-07-06 }}</ref> For Scorsese, Saul and Elaine Bass<ref>{{cite news|last=Sloman|first=Tony|title=OBITUARY : Saul Bass|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/obituary--saul-bass-1307494.html|newspaper=The Independent|date=30 April 1996}}</ref> created title sequences for ''[[Goodfellas]]'' (1990), ''[[Cape Fear (1991 film)|Cape Fear]]'' (1991), ''[[The Age of Innocence (1993 film)|The Age of Innocence]]'' (1993), and ''[[Casino (film)|Casino]]'' (1995), their last title sequence. This later work with [[Martin Scorsese]] saw the Basses move away from the optical techniques that Saul had pioneered and move into the use of computerized effects. The Basses' title sequences featured new and innovative methods of production and startling [[graphic design]].\n\nScreenwriter [[Nicholas Pileggi]] said of Saul and Elaine Bass, \"You write a book of 300 to 400 pages and then you boil it down to a script of maybe 100 to 150 pages. Eventually you have the pleasure of seeing that the Basses have knocked you right out of the ballpark. They have boiled it down to four minutes flat.\"<ref>Jennifer Bass and Pat Kirkham, Saul Bass: A Life in Film & Design, Laurence King Publishing, 2011, pg.263</ref>\n\nIn a sense, all modern opening title sequences that introduce the mood or theme of a film can be seen as a legacy of the Basses' innovative work. In particular, title sequences for some recent movies and television series, especially those whose setting is during the 1960s, have purposely emulated the graphic style of Saul Bass's animated sequences from the 1950s. Some examples of title sequences that pay homage to Bass's graphics and animated title sequences are ''[[Catch Me If You Can]]'' (2002),<ref>[http://www.artofthetitle.com/2011/08/22/catch-me-if-you-can/ Interview with Olivier Kuntzel and Florence Degas, designers of the ''Catch Me If You Can'' title sequence]. Artofthetitle.com. Retrieved 2011-12-10</ref> ''[[X-Men: First Class]]'' (2011),<ref>[http://www.watchthetitles.com/articles/00223-X_Men_First_Class/ Interview with Simon Clowes, designer of the ''X-Men First Class'' title sequence]. Watchthetitles.com</ref> and the openings to the AMC series ''[[Mad Men]]''<ref>[http://www.amc.com/shows/mad-men/talk/2008/03/qa-title-design Mad Men Q&A: ''Mad Men'' Title Designers Mark Gardner and Steve Fuller] Retrieved 2011-12-19</ref> and TBS's ''[[Conan (talk show)|Conan]]''.<ref name=\"conantitle\">{{cite web |url=http://magazine.creativecow.net/article/designing-conan |title=Designing Conan |last=Ashe |first=Rob |work=Creative Cow |page=1|accessdate=June 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Selected film title sequences==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n* ''[[Carmen Jones (film)|Carmen Jones]]'' (1954)\n* ''[[The Big Knife]]'' (1955)\n* ''[[The Man with the Golden Arm]]'' (1955)\n* ''[[The Racers]]'' (1955)\n* ''[[The Seven Year Itch]]'' (1955)\n* ''[[The Shrike (film)|The Shrike]]'' (1955)\n* ''[[Around the World in 80 Days (1956 film)|Around the World in Eighty Days]]'' (1956)\n* ''[[Storm Center]]'' (1956)\n* ''[[Attack (1956 film)|Attack]]'' (1956)\n* ''[[Edge of the City]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[Saint Joan (1957 film)|Saint Joan]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[The Pride and the Passion]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[The Young Stranger]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[Bonjour Tristesse (film)|Bonjour Tristesse]]'' (1958)\n* ''[[Cowboy (1958 film)|Cowboy]]'' (1958)\n* ''[[Vertigo (film)|Vertigo]]'' (1958)\n* ''[[The Big Country]]'' (1958)\n{{col-break}}\n* ''[[Anatomy of a Murder]]'' (1959)\n* ''[[North by Northwest]]'' (1959)\n* ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[Spartacus (film)|Spartacus]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[The Facts of Life (film)|The Facts of Life]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[Exodus (1960 film)|Exodus]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[Ocean's 11]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[West Side Story (1961 film)|West Side Story]]'' (1961)\n* ''[[Something Wild (1961 film)|Something Wild]]'' (1961)\n* ''[[Advise & Consent]]'' (1962)\n* ''[[Walk on the Wild Side (film)|Walk on the Wild Side]]'' (1962)\n* ''[[The Victors (film)|The Victors]]'' (1963)\n* ''[[Nine Hours to Rama]]'' (1963)\n* ''[[It's a Mad, Mad, Mad, Mad World]]'' (1963)\n* ''[[The Cardinal]]'' (1963)\n* ''[[In Harm's Way]]'' (1965)\n* ''[[Bunny Lake Is Missing]]'' (1965)\n{{col-break}}\n* ''[[Grand Prix (1966 film)|Grand Prix]]'' (1966)\n* ''[[Not with My Wife, You Don't!]]'' (1966)\n* ''[[Seconds (1966 film)|Seconds]]'' (1966)\n* ''[[Such Good Friends]]'' (1971)\n* ''[[That's Entertainment, Part II]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[Broadcast News (film)|Broadcast News]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Big (film)|Big]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[The War of the Roses (film)|The War of the Roses]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Goodfellas]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Cape Fear (1991 film)|Cape Fear]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Doc Hollywood]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Mr. Saturday Night]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[The Age of Innocence (1993 film)|The Age of Innocence]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Higher Learning]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Casino (film)|Casino]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[A Personal Journey with Martin Scorsese Through American Movies]]'' (1995)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Logos and other designs==\nBass was responsible for some of the best-remembered, most iconic logos in North America, including both the Bell Telephone logo (1969) and successor AT&T globe (1983). Other well-known designs were [[Continental Airlines]] (1968), [[Dixie Cup|Dixie]] (1969) and [[United Airlines]] (1974). Later, he would produce logos for a number of Japanese companies as well.\n\nSelected logos by Saul Bass and their respective dates (note that the links shown point to articles on the entities themselves, and not necessarily to the logos):\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[Alcoa]] (1963)\n*[[Ajinomoto]] (1973)\n*[[AT&T Corporation]] (1969 and 1983)\n*[[Avery International]] (1975)\n*[[Boys & Girls Clubs of America]] (1978)\n*[[Celanese]] (1965)\n*[[Continental Airlines]] (1968)<ref name=\"Serling\">Serling, Robert J. (1974). ''Maverick: The story of Robert Six and Continental Airlines''. Doubleday & Company. {{ISBN|0-385-04057-1}}.</ref>\n*[[Dixie Cup|Dixie]] (1969)\n*[[Frontier Airlines (1950\u20131986)|Frontier Airlines]] (1978)\n*Fuller Paints (1962)\n*[[Geffen Records]] (1980)\n*[[General Foods]] (1984)\n*[[Girl Scouts of the USA]] (1978)\n*[[Japan Energy Corporation]] (1993)\n*[[J. Paul Getty Trust]] (1993)\n*Kibun Foods (1984)\n*[[KOS\u00c9|Kose Cosmetics]] (1991)\n*[[Lawry's Foods]] (1959)\n*Minami Sports (1991)\n*[[Minolta]] (1978 and 1981)\n*[[NCR Corporation]] (1996)\n*[[Quaker Oats]] (1969)\n*[[Rockwell International]] (1968)\n*[[Security Pacific Bank]] (1966)\n*[[United Airlines]] (1974)\n*[[United Way of America|United Way]] (1972)\n*[[Postage stamps and postal history of the United States|US postage stamp]], \"Science and Industry\" (1983)<ref>[http://www.katranpress.com/stamps_bass_1_1.html \"A postage stamp by Saul Bass\"]. Retrieved 2011-04-02.</ref>\n*[[Warner Communications]] (1974)\n*[[Wienerschnitzel]] (1978)\n*[[Wesson Oil]] (1964)\n*[[YWCA]] (1988)\n{{div col end}}\n\nAn analysis of a sample of Bass's corporate logos in 2011 found them to have an unusual longevity. The most common cause of the end of a Bass corporate logo (in the selection analyzed) was the demise or merge of the company, rather than a corporate logo redesign. The average lifespan of a Bass logo is more than 34 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adage.com/article/behind-the-work/a-favorite-saul-bass-logos/241361/ |title=A Few of Our Favorite Saul Bass Logos |first=Rupal |last=Parekh |date=May 8, 2013 |work=[[Advertising Age]]}}</ref> In 2014, [[Frontier Airlines]] resurrected the stylized F logo originally designed for Frontier by Bass in 1978, and discontinued when the airlines when bankrupt in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://skift.com/2014/09/10/frontier-airlines-looks-to-the-past-to-set-designs-on-its-future// |title=Frontier Airlines Looks to the Past to Set Designs on Its Future|first=Brian |last=Sumers |date=September 10, 2014 |work=[[Skift]]}}</ref>\n\n==Movie posters==\n[[File:The Man with the Golden Arm poster.jpg|upright|thumb|''[[The Man with the Golden Arm]]'' poster designed by Bass]]\nSaul Bass designed emblematic movie posters that transformed the visuals of film advertising. Before Bass's seminal poster for ''[[The Man with the Golden Arm]]'' (1955), movie posters were dominated by depictions of key scenes or characters from the film, often both juxtaposed with each other. Bass's posters, however, typically developed simplified, symbolic designs that visually communicated key essential elements of the film. For example, his poster for ''The Man with the Golden Arm'', with a jagged arm and off-kilter typography, starkly communicates the protagonist's struggle with heroin addiction. Bass's iconic ''[[Vertigo (film)|Vertigo]]'' (1958) poster, with its stylized figures sucked down into the nucleus of a spiral vortex, captures the anxiety and disorientation central to the film. His poster for ''[[Anatomy of a Murder]]'' (1959), featuring the silhouette of a corpse jarringly dissected into seven pieces, makes both a pun on the film's title and captures the moral ambiguities within which this court room drama is immersed.\n\nHe created some of his best known posters for films directed by [[Otto Preminger]], [[Alfred Hitchcock]], [[Billy Wilder]], and [[Stanley Kubrick]] among others. His last commissioned film poster was created for [[Steven Spielberg]]'s ''[[Schindler's List]]'' (1993), but it was never distributed.<ref>Kirkham, Pat & Jennifer Bass (2011) ''Saul Bass: A Life in Film & Design'' (pp. 406 and 420). London: Laurence King</ref> His poster work spanned five decades and inspired numerous other poster and graphic designers. Bass's film posters are characterized by a distinctive typography and minimalistic style.\n\nSelected posters by Saul Bass, and their respective dates:\n\n===1950s===\n[[File:Vertigomovie restoration.jpg|thumb|upright|''[[Vertigo (film)|Vertigo]]'' poster designed by Bass]]\n* ''[[Carmen Jones (film)|Carmen Jones]]'' (1954)\n* ''[[The Man with the Golden Arm]]'' (1955)\n* ''[[Edge of the City]]'' (1956)\n* ''[[Storm Center]]'' (1956)\n* ''[[Love in the Afternoon (1957 film)|Love in the Afternoon]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[Saint Joan (1957 film)|Saint Joan]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[Bonjour tristesse (film)|Bonjour tristesse]]'' (1958)\n* ''[[The Big Country]]'' (1958) (style b poster)\n* ''[[Vertigo (film)|Vertigo]]'' (1958)\n* ''[[Anatomy of a Murder]]'' (1959)\n\n===1960s===\n[[File:AnatomyMurder2.jpg|upright|thumb|''[[Anatomy of a Murder]]'' poster designed by Bass]]\n* ''[[Exodus (1960 film)|Exodus]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[The Magnificent Seven]]'' (1960) (design not used)\n* ''[[One, Two, Three]]'' (1961)\n* ''[[Advise & Consent (film)|Advise & Consent]]'' (1962)\n* ''[[It's a Mad, Mad, Mad, Mad World]]'' (1963)\n* ''[[The Cardinal]]'' (1963)\n* ''[[In Harm's Way]]'' (1964)\n* ''[[Bunny Lake Is Missing]]'' (1965)\n* ''[[The Firemen's Ball]]'' (1967)\n* ''[[The Two of Us (1967 film)|The Two of Us]]'' (1967)\n* ''[[Why Man Creates]]'' (1968)\n* ''Very Happy Alexander'' (1969)\n\n===1970s===\n[[File:The Shining (1980).png|upright|thumb|''[[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]'' poster designed by Bass ([[The Shining (film)#Ad campaigns|which he intended to be red, but was changed by Stanley Kubrick to yellow]])<ref name=filmartgallery>{{cite web |url=https://filmartgallery.com/collections/the-shining |title=The Shining Vintage Movie Posters {{!}} Original Film Posters @ Film Art Gallery |website=filmartgallery.com |access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>]]\n* ''[[Such Good Friends]]'' (1971)\n* ''[[Rosebud (1975 film)|Rosebud]]'' (1975)\n* ''Brothers'' (1977)\n* ''Notes on the Popular Arts'' (1977)\n* ''Bass on Titles'' (1978)\n* ''[[The Human Factor (1979 film)|The Human Factor]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[The Solar Film]]'' (1979)\n\n===1980s and 1990s===\n[[File:Theatrical release poster (not distributed) designed by Saul Bass for the film, Schindler's List (1993).jpg|upright|thumb|''[[Schindler's List]]'' poster designed by Bass, his last commissioned film poster (not distributed).]]\n* ''[[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]'' (1980)\n* ''[[Return from the River Kwai]]'' (1989) (not distributed)\n* ''[[Schindler's List]]'' (1993) (rejected poster)\n\nHe received an unintentionally backhanded tribute in 1995, when [[Spike Lee]]'s film ''[[Clockers (film)|Clockers]]'' was promoted by a poster that was strikingly similar to Bass's 1959 work for Preminger's film ''[[Anatomy of a Murder]]''. Designer Art Sims claimed that it was made as an homage, but Bass regarded it as theft.<ref>Schaefer, Stephen (September 08, 1995). [http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,298637,00.html \"Poster Imposter\"]. ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''. 2011-04-02.</ref> Many film posters have been considered to be homages to Saul Bass's posters. Some recent examples include the theatrical release poster for ''[[Burn After Reading]]'' (2008) which incorporates Bass's typography and style of figurative minimalism,<ref>{{cite web|title=Burn After Reading Poster Inspired by Saul Bass|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/burn-after-reading-poster-inspired-by-saul-bass/|publisher=/Film|date=June 17, 2008}}</ref> and a poster for ''[[Precious (film)|Precious]]'' (2009) which includes elements from several of Bass's posters, including ''[[Anatomy of a Murder]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dieselation.com/?tag=saul-bass |title=Saul Bass |publisher=Dieselation |date=2009-05-30 |accessdate=2012-06-06}}</ref> The cover art for [[The White Stripes]]' single ''[[The Hardest Button to Button]]'' is clearly inspired by the Bass poster for ''[[The Man with the Golden Arm]]''.<ref>[http://www.voxpopmag.com/le-magazine/16961-sound-and-vision-the-white-stripes/ SOUND AND VISION: THE WHITE STRIPES-VoxPop]</ref>\n\nThe comic book artist [[J. H. Williams III]]'s designs for the [[Batman]] story [[Batman R.I.P.|\"The Black Glove\"]] pay homage to Bass's designs as well.<ref>Singer, Marc. ''Grant Morrison: Combining the Worlds of Contemporary Comics''. (Univ. Press of Mississippi, Jackson, MS, 2012) p. 272. [https://books.google.com/books?id=ZVB2LK-FAusC&pg=PA272 Link at Google Books].</ref>\n\nIn addition to movie posters, Bass designed numerous posters for film festivals, and several magazine, book, and album covers. He also designed five Academy Award Presentation posters and the [[Student Academy Award]] for the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]].<ref>[http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/about/awards/saa.html \"Student Academy Award\"]. Oscars.org. Retrieved 2011-12-20.</ref> In 1962 he illustrated his only children's book, ''Henri's Walk to Paris'', written by Lenore Klein.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grainedit.com/2007/12/03/henris-walk-to-paris-designed-by-saul-bass |title=grain edit \u00b7 Henri's walk to Paris : Designed by Saul Bass |publisher=Grainedit.com |date=2012-02-14 |accessdate=2012-06-06}}</ref>\n\n==Filmmaker==\nDuring the 1960s, Bass was asked by directors and producers to produce not only title sequences for their films, but also to visualize and storyboard key scenes and sequences within them. Bass has the unusual credit of \"visual consultant\" or \"pictorial consultant\" on five films. For ''[[Spartacus (film)|Spartacus]]'' (1960), Bass as \"visual consultant\" designed key elements of the gladiator school and storyboarded the final battle between slaves and Romans. [[John Frankenheimer]], the director of ''[[Grand Prix (1966 film)|Grand Prix]]'' (1966), had Bass storyboard, direct, and edit all but one of the racing sequences for his film. For ''[[West Side Story (1961 film)|West Side Story]]'' (1961) Bass filmed the prologue, storyboarded the opening dance sequence, and created the ending title sequence.<ref name=\"kirkham2011\"/>\n\nIt is Bass's credited role as \"pictorial consultant\" for Alfred Hitchcock on ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' (1960); however, that has caused some controversy and debate. Bass claimed that he participated in directing the highlight scene of ''Psycho'', the tightly edited shower-murder sequence, though several on set at the time (including star [[Janet Leigh]]) disputed this claim.<ref>[http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2014/02/20/psycho_shower_scene_directed_by_saul_bass_watch_storyboards_side_by_side.html/ Harris, Aisha (February 20, 2014) \"Did Saul Bass Direct the Shower Scene in ''Psycho''?\"] Slate.com. Retrieved 2014-2-23</ref>\n\nThe research of several film scholars on Hitchcock's production of ''Psycho'' validates the claim that Bass in his capacity as a graphic artist did indeed have a significant influence on the visual design and pacing of that famous scene. Hitchcock had asked Bass to design and produce storyboards for the shower murder scene and for some other scenes in the film. For this, Bass received a credit as Pictorial Consultant as well as Title Designer. Janet Leigh told [[Donald Spoto]] that \"the planning of the shower scene was left up to Saul Bass, and Hitchcock followed his storyboard precisely. Because of this ... [the shooting] went very professionally,\"<ref>Spoto, Donald (1999 [1983]). ''The Dark Side Of Genius: The Life Of Alfred Hitchcock''. New York: Da Capo Press. (pp. 454\u2013455)</ref> and she told [[Stephen Rebello]] that \"Mr. Hitchcock showed Saul Bass's storyboards to me quite proudly, telling me in exact detail how he was going to shoot the scene from Saul's plans\".<ref>Rebello, Stephen (1990). ''Alfred Hitchcock and the Making of Psycho''. New York: St. Martin's Griffin. (p. 102) {{ISBN|0-312-20785-9}}.</ref>\n\nBill Krohn has noted that Bass's 48 story board panels for the scene introduced all the key aspects of the final shower murder scene \u2013 most notably, the fact that the attacker appears as a silhouette, close-ups of a slashing knife, the shower curtain torn down, a shot of the shower head from below, Marion's desperate outstretched arm, and the famous shot of the transition from the drain hole of the bathtub to Marion Crane's dead eye. Krohn notes that this final transition is highly reminiscent of Bass's iris titles for ''[[Vertigo (film)|Vertigo]]''.<ref name=Krohn>Krohn, Bill (2003). ''Hitchcock at Work''. (pp. London: Phaidon Press. (p. 231)</ref> Krohn also concludes that Bass did not literally direct the shower scene, proving Hitchcock's presence on the set throughout the shooting of that scene.<ref name=Krohn/>\n\nBass introduced the idea of using a montage of fast cuts and tight framing to render a violent, bloody murder as an impressionistic and nearly bloodless one. Hitchcock felt uncertain about Bass's conception of the scene fearing that audiences might not accept such a stylized and quickly cut sequence. In an interview with film historian [[Pat Kirkham]], Bass recalled, \"Having designed and storyboarded the shower sequence, I showed it to Hitch. He was uneasy about it. It was very un-Hitchcockian in character. He never used that kind of quick cutting; he loved the long shot\".<ref name=\"kirkham2011\"/>\n\nTo convince Hitchcock that the scene would work as planned, eight days before shooting of the final shower scene, Bass used a newsreel camera and Janet Leigh's stand-in [[Marli Renfro]] to shoot footage on the set to plan the shots in more detail. Working with Hitchcock's editor [[George Tomasini]], he edited this footage following the storyboards to show Hitchcock how the scene could work. In the end, Hitchcock gave his approval but, according to Kirkham, made two additions: a spray of blood on the chest of Marion Crane/Janet Leigh as she slides down the tiles, and a close-up of her belly getting stabbed.<ref name=\"kirkham2011\"/>\n\nIn 1964, Saul and his wife and creative partner [[Elaine Bass|Elaine]] directed the short film ''The Searching Eye'' shown during the [[1964 New York World's Fair]], co-produced with [[Sy Wexler]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pyramidmedia.com/homepage/search-by-title/humanities/searching-eye-detail.html|title=HUMANITIES : Searching Eye, The|website=www.pyramidmedia.com}}</ref> The Basses also directed a short documentary film called ''[[Why Man Creates]]''<ref>[https://www.bcdb.com/cartoon/55396-Why-Man-Creates Why Man Creates (1968) Theatrical Cartoon - BCDB]</ref> which won the [[Academy Award for Documentary Short Subject]] in 1968.<ref>[http://nightflight.com/why-man-creates-saul-basss-short-film-on-the-nature-of-creativity/ \u201cWhy Man Creates\u201d: Saul Bass\u2019s short film on the nature of creativity\u2014Night Flight]</ref>  An abbreviated version of that film was broadcast on the first episode of the television newsmagazine ''[[60 Minutes]]''. In 2002, this film was selected for preservation in the United States [[National Film Registry]] by the [[Library of Congress]] as being \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/prn-02-176/librarian-of-congress-adds-25-films-to-national-film-registry/2002-12-17/|title=Librarian of Congress Adds 25 Films to National Film Registry|website=Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. 20540 USA}}</ref> Saul, in collaboration with his wife and creative partner [[Elaine Bass|Elaine]], directed several other short films, two of which were nominated for [[Academy Award]] Oscars; ''[[Academy Award for Best Live Action Short Film|Notes on the Popular Arts]]'' in 1977,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pyramidmedia.com/homepage/search-by-title/humanities/notes-on-the-popular-arts-detail.html|title=HUMANITIES : Notes On The Popular Arts|website=www.pyramidmedia.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/notes-on-the-popular-arts-v35724|title=Notes on the Popular Arts (1978) - Elaine Bass, Saul Bass &#124; Synopsis, Characteristics, Moods, Themes and Related|website=AllMovie}}</ref> and ''[[The Solar Film]]'' in 1979, the latter for which [[Robert Redford]] was the executive producer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pyramidmedia.com/homepage/search-by-title/academy-awards/solar-film-detail.html|title=ACADEMY AWARD : Solar Film, The|website=www.pyramidmedia.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thescienceofcreativity.com/653|title=The Science of Creativity - The Solar Film|website=www.thescienceofcreativity.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, Saul Bass made his only feature-length film as a director, the visually splendid though little-known [[science fiction film|science fiction]] film ''[[Phase IV]]'', a \"Quiet, haunting, beautiful, ... and largely overlooked, science-fiction masterwork\".<ref>Scalzo, Thomas (August 8, 2005). [http://www.notcoming.com/reviews/phase4/ \"''Phase IV'' (review)\"]. ''[[Not Coming to a Theater Near You]]'' (notcoming.com). Retrieved 2008-10-16.</ref> The moving image collection of Saul Bass is held at the Academy Film Archive and consists of 2,700 items. The film material at the Academy Film Archive is complemented by material in the Saul Bass papers at the Academy's Margaret Herrick Library.<ref>{{cite web|title=Saul Bass Collection|url=http://www.oscars.org/film-archive/collections/saul-bass-collection|website=Academy Film Archive}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nOn May 8, 2013, Bass's 93rd birthday was celebrated by a [[Google Doodle]], which featured the tune \"[[Unsquare Dance]]\" by [[Dave Brubeck]].<ref>[http://www.csmonitor.com/Innovation/2013/0508/Saul-Bass-Designer-artist-and-auteur-of-the-opening-credits \"Saul Bass: Designer, artist, and auteur of the opening credits (+video)\"] by Matthew Shaer, ''[[The Christian Science Monitor]]'', May 8, 2013</ref><ref>{{YouTube|64lDaAmpvSo|Doodle for Saul Bass' 93rd Birthday}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Portal|Biography|Film}}\n\n* [[Elaine Makatura Bass]]\n* [[Motion graphics]]\n* [[Paul Rand]]\n* [[Richard Amsel]]\n* [[Tom Jung]]\n* [[Frank McCarthy (artist)|Frank McCarthy]]\n* [[Bob Peak]]\n* [[Drew Struzan]]\n* [[Howard Terpning]]\n* [[Pablo Ferro]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Kirkham, Pat and Jennifer Bass (2011). ''Saul Bass: A Life in Film & Design''. London: Laurence King. {{ISBN|978-1-85669-752-1}}.\n* Tomislav Terek (2001). ''Saul Bass on Titles: Film Titles Revealed''. Defunkt Century. {{ISBN|1-903792-00-2}}.\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0000866}}\n*[https://filmartgallery.com/pages/saul-bass-archive Saul Bass Archive] at [https://www.filmartgallery.com FilmArt Gallery]\n*[http://www.saulbassposterarchive.com/ Saul Bass Poster Archive] The Saul Bass Estate\n*[http://www.notcoming.com/saulbass/index.php/ Titles Designed by Saul Bass (still sequences & commentary)]\n*[http://www.artofthetitle.com/designer/saul-bass/ Saul Bass Title Sequences on Art of the Title]\n*[http://www.37signals.com/svn/posts/917-title-sequences-from-saul-bass-the-master-of-film-title-design Title Sequences from Saul Bass (videos & commentary)]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2013/may/08/saul-bass-title-sequence-ten-best?CMP=EMCFLMEML1672 Saul Bass title sequences: ten of the best] compiled by ''The Guardian''\n* [http://catalog.oscars.org/vwebv/holdingsInfo?bibId=68170 Saul Bass papers], Margaret Herrick Library, Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bass, Saul}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:AIGA medalists]]\n[[Category:American graphic designers]]\n[[Category:American typographers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in California]]\n[[Category:Deaths from lymphoma]]\n[[Category:Directors of Best Documentary Short Subject Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Film and television title designers]]\n[[Category:Film poster artists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American artists]]\n[[Category:Logo designers]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:James Monroe High School (New York City) alumni]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn College alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-move-indef|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American graphic designer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Saul Bass\n| image = Saul Bass.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1920|5|8}}\n| birth_place = [[The Bronx]], New York, U.S.\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1996|4|25|1920|5|8}}\n| death_place = [[Los Angeles]], California, U.S.\n| nationality = American\n| known_for = \n| occupation = [[Graphic designer]], title designer, film director\n| awards = {{ubl|Academy Award, Best Documentary, Short Subjects, ''Why Man Creates'' (1968)|Honorary Doctorate, [[Otis College of Art and Design]](1986)}}\n|spouse= {{ubl|Ruth Cooper (1938\u20131960)|[[Elaine Makatura Bass]] (1961\u20131996; his death)}}\n| children = 4\n}}\n\n'''Saul Bass''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u00e6|s}}; May 8, 1920&nbsp;\u2013 April 25, 1996) was an American [[graphic designer]] and [[Academy Awards|Oscar]]-winning filmmaker, best known for his design of motion-picture [[title sequence]]s, [[film poster]]s, and [[logo|corporate logos]].\n\nDuring his 40-year career, Bass worked for some of Hollywood's most prominent filmmakers, including [[Alfred Hitchcock]], [[Otto Preminger]], [[Billy Wilder]], [[Stanley Kubrick]] and [[Martin Scorsese]]. Among his most famous [[title sequence]]s are the animated paper cut-out of a heroin addict's arm for Preminger's ''[[The Man with the Golden Arm]]'', the credits racing up and down what eventually becomes a high-angle shot of a skyscraper in Hitchcock's ''[[North by Northwest]]'', and the disjointed text that races together and apart in ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]''.\n\nBass designed some of the most iconic corporate logos in North America, including the [[Bell System]] logo in 1969, as well as [[American Telephone & Telegraph Company|AT&T]]'s globe logo in 1983 after the [[Bell System divestiture|breakup of the Bell System]]. He also designed [[Continental Airlines]]' 1968 jet stream logo and [[United Airlines]]' 1974 tulip logo, which became some of the most recognized airline industry logos of the era. He died from [[non-Hodgkin's lymphoma]] in Los Angeles on April 25, 1996, at the age of 75.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1996-04-27-9604260612-story.html|title=SAUL BASS, 75, LOGO AND TRADEMARK DESIGNER|first=Los Angeles|last=Times|website=Sun-Sentinel.com}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSaul Bass was born on May 8, 1920 in [[the Bronx]], New York, United States, to Eastern European Jewish immigrant parents. He graduated from [[James Monroe High School (New York)|James Monroe High School]] in [[the Bronx]] and studied part-time at the [[Art Students League of New York|Art Students League]] in Manhattan until attending night classes with [[Gy\u00f6rgy Kepes]] at [[Brooklyn College]].<ref name=\"kirkham2011\">{{cite journal|last=Kirkham|first=Pat|title=Reassessing the Saul Bass and Alfred Hitchcock Collaboration|date=10 February 2011|volume=18|url=http://www.west86th.bgc.bard.edu/articles/kirkham-bass-hitchcock.html|journal=West 86th}}</ref> In 1938, Saul married Ruth Cooper and they had two children, Robert in 1942 and Andrea in 1946.<ref name=\"horak\">{{cite book|last1=Horak|first1=Jan-Christopher|title=Saul Bass: Anatomy of Film Design|date=2014|publisher=The University of Kentucky Press|isbn=0813147190}}</ref>\n\nHe began his time in Hollywood in the 1940s, designing print advertisements for films including ''[[Champion (1949 film)|Champion]]'' (1949), ''[[Death of a Salesman (1951 film)|Death of a Salesman]]'' (1951) and ''[[The Moon Is Blue]]'' (1953), directed by Otto Preminger. His next collaboration with Preminger was to design a [[film poster]] for his 1954 film ''[[Carmen Jones (film)|Carmen Jones]]''. Preminger was so impressed with Bass's work that he asked him to produce the title sequence as well. This was when Bass first saw the opportunity to create a title sequence which would ultimately enhance the experience of the audience and contribute to the mood and the theme of the movie within the opening moments. Bass was one of the first to realize the creative potential of the opening and closing credits of a movie.\n\n==Film title sequences==\nBass became widely known in the film industry after creating the title sequence for [[Otto Preminger]]'s ''[[The Man with the Golden Arm]]'' (1955). The subject of the film was a jazz musician's struggle to overcome his [[heroin addiction]], a taboo subject in the mid-1950s. Bass decided to create an innovative [[title sequence]] to match the film's controversial subject. He chose the arm as the central image, as it is a strong image relating to heroin addiction. The titles featured an animated, white on black paper cut-out arm of a heroin addict. As he hoped, it caused quite a sensation.\n[[File:Anatomy Of A Murder Title Sequence.jpg|thumb|Screen image from Saul Bass's title sequence from ''Anatomy Of A Murder'']]\nFor Alfred Hitchcock, Bass provided effective, memorable title sequences, inventing a new type of [[kinetic typography]], for ''[[North by Northwest]]'' (1959), ''[[Vertigo (film)|Vertigo]]'' (1958), working with [[John Whitney (animator)|John Whitney]], and ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' (1960). It was this kind of innovative, revolutionary work that made Bass a revered [[graphic designer]]. Before the advent of Bass's title sequences in the 1950s, titles were generally static, separate from the movie, and it was common for them to be projected onto the cinema curtains, the curtains only being raised right before the first scene of the movie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.granneman.com/2011/04/05/saul-bass-changed-how-audiences-view-movie-credits/ |title=GranneBlog \u00bb Saul Bass changed how audiences view movie credits |publisher=Blog.granneman.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-06}}</ref> In 1960, Bass wrote an article for ''Graphis'' magazine called \"Film Titles \u2013 a New Field for the Graphic Designer,\" which has been revered as a milestone for \"the consecration of the movie credit sequence as a design object.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Film Titles \u2013 a New Field for the Graphic Designer|last=Bass|first=Saul|date=1960|work=Graphis|issue=89|volume=16|access-date=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Straw|first=Will|year=2010|title=Letters of Introduction: Film Credits and Cityscapes|journal=Design and Culture|volume=2|issue=2}}</ref> One of the most studied film credit designers, Bass is known for integrating a stylistic coherence between the designs and the films in which they appear.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nBass once described his main goal for his title sequences as being to \"try to reach for a simple, visual phrase that tells you what the picture is all about and evokes the essence of the story\".<ref>Kael, Pauline. \"One, Two, Three.\" ''[[Film Quarterly]]'' Vol. 15, No. 3. (Spring, 1962): 62\u201365</ref> Another philosophy that Bass described as influencing his title sequences was the goal of getting the audience to see familiar parts of their world in an unfamiliar way. Examples of this or what he described as \"making the ordinary extraordinary\" can be seen in ''[[Walk on the Wild Side (film)|Walk on the Wild Side]]'' (1962) where an ordinary cat becomes a mysterious prowling predator, and in ''[[Nine Hours to Rama]]'' (1963) where the interior workings of a clock become an expansive new landscape.<ref>Bass, Saul (1977) ''Bass on Titles''. Pyramid Films. Santa Monica, CA</ref> In the 1950s, Saul Bass used a variety of techniques, from cut-out animation for ''[[Anatomy of a Murder]]'' (1958), to fully animated mini-movies such as the epilogue for the [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture Oscar]] winner ''[[Around the World in 80 Days (1956 film)|Around the World in 80 Days]]'' (1956), and live-action sequences.\n\nIn 1955, [[Elaine Makatura Bass|Elaine Makatura]] came to work with Bass in his Los Angeles office. By 1960, with the opening to ''[[Spartacus (film)|Spartacus]]'', she was directing and producing title sequences, and in 1961 the two married, beginning more than 40 years of close collaboration. After the birth of their children, Jennifer in 1964 and Jeffrey in 1967, they concentrated on their family, film directing, and title sequences. Saul and Elaine designed title sequences for more than 40 years, continuously experimenting with a variety of innovative techniques and effects, from [[Bunraku]]-style maneuvers in ''[[Spartacus]]'' (1960), live-action sequences in ''[[Walk on the Wild Side (film)|Walk On The Wild Side]]'' (1962), to time-lapse photography in ''[[The Age of Innocence]]'' (1993), and even chopped liver in ''[[Mr. Saturday Night]]'' (1992). Their live-action opening title sequences often served as prologues to their films and transitioned seamlessly into their opening scenes. These \"time before\" title sequences either compress or expand time with startling results. The title sequence to ''[[Grand Prix (1966 film)|Grand Prix]]'' (1966) portrays the moments before the opening race in Monte Carlo, the title sequence to ''[[The Big Country]]'' (1958) depicts the days it takes a stage coach to travel to a remote Western town, and the opening montage title sequence to ''[[The Victors (film)|The Victors]]'' (1963) chronicles the twenty-seven years between World War I and the middle of World War II, where the film begins.\n\nFrom the mid-1960s to the late '80s, Saul and Elaine moved away from main titles to focus on filmmaking and their children. About this time away from title design, Saul said:<ref>{{cite web|title=Saul Bass|url=http://www.artofthetitle.com/designer/saul-bass/|website=Art of the Title|accessdate=13 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Elaine and I feel we are there to serve the film and to approach the task with a sense of responsibility. We saw a lot of pyrotechnics and fun and games and I suppose we lost interest. At the same time, an increasing number of directors now sought to open their own films in ambitious ways rather than hire someone else to do it. Whatever the reasons, the result was \"Fade Out.\" We did not worry about it: we had too many other interesting projects to get on with. Equally, because we still loved the process of making titles, we were happy to take it up again when asked. \"Fade In\"...<ref>Jennifer Bass and Pat Kirkham, ''Saul Bass: A Life in Film & Design'', Laurence King Publishing, 2011, p. 264</ref>}}\n\nIn the 1980s, Saul and Elaine were rediscovered by [[James L. Brooks]] and [[Martin Scorsese]], who had grown up admiring their film work.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/filmtvinfo/library/eventsexh/past/saulbass/biography.html |title=Library &#124; Exhibitions and Events &#124; Saul Bass: biography |publisher=BFI |date=2012-05-11 |accessdate=2012-06-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706073216/http://www.bfi.org.uk/filmtvinfo/library/eventsexh/past/saulbass/biography.html |archivedate=2011-07-06 }}</ref> For Scorsese, Saul and Elaine Bass<ref>{{cite news|last=Sloman|first=Tony|title=OBITUARY : Saul Bass|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/obituary--saul-bass-1307494.html|newspaper=The Independent|date=30 April 1996}}</ref> created title sequences for ''[[Goodfellas]]'' (1990), ''[[Cape Fear (1991 film)|Cape Fear]]'' (1991), ''[[The Age of Innocence (1993 film)|The Age of Innocence]]'' (1993), and ''[[Casino (film)|Casino]]'' (1995), their last title sequence. This later work with [[Martin Scorsese]] saw the Basses move away from the optical techniques that Saul had pioneered and move into the use of computerized effects. The Basses' title sequences featured new and innovative methods of production and startling [[graphic design]].\n\nScreenwriter [[Nicholas Pileggi]] said of Saul and Elaine Bass, \"You write a book of 300 to 400 pages and then you boil it down to a script of maybe 100 to 150 pages. Eventually you have the pleasure of seeing that the Basses have knocked you right out of the ballpark. They have boiled it down to four minutes flat.\"<ref>Jennifer Bass and Pat Kirkham, Saul Bass: A Life in Film & Design, Laurence King Publishing, 2011, pg.263</ref>\n\nIn a sense, all modern opening title sequences that introduce the mood or theme of a film can be seen as a legacy of the Basses' innovative work. In particular, title sequences for some recent movies and television series, especially those whose setting is during the 1960s, have purposely emulated the graphic style of Saul Bass's animated sequences from the 1950s. Some examples of title sequences that pay homage to Bass's graphics and animated title sequences are ''[[Catch Me If You Can]]'' (2002),<ref>[http://www.artofthetitle.com/2011/08/22/catch-me-if-you-can/ Interview with Olivier Kuntzel and Florence Degas, designers of the ''Catch Me If You Can'' title sequence]. Artofthetitle.com. Retrieved 2011-12-10</ref> ''[[X-Men: First Class]]'' (2011),<ref>[http://www.watchthetitles.com/articles/00223-X_Men_First_Class/ Interview with Simon Clowes, designer of the ''X-Men First Class'' title sequence]. Watchthetitles.com</ref> and the openings to the AMC series ''[[Mad Men]]''<ref>[http://www.amc.com/shows/mad-men/talk/2008/03/qa-title-design Mad Men Q&A: ''Mad Men'' Title Designers Mark Gardner and Steve Fuller] Retrieved 2011-12-19</ref> and TBS's ''[[Conan (talk show)|Conan]]''.<ref name=\"conantitle\">{{cite web |url=http://magazine.creativecow.net/article/designing-conan |title=Designing Conan |last=Ashe |first=Rob |work=Creative Cow |page=1|accessdate=June 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Selected film title sequences==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n* ''[[Carmen Jones (film)|Carmen Jones]]'' (1954)\n* ''[[The Big Knife]]'' (1955)\n* ''[[The Man with the Golden Arm]]'' (1955)\n* ''[[The Racers]]'' (1955)\n* ''[[The Seven Year Itch]]'' (1955)\n* ''[[The Shrike (film)|The Shrike]]'' (1955)\n* ''[[Around the World in 80 Days (1956 film)|Around the World in Eighty Days]]'' (1956)\n* ''[[Storm Center]]'' (1956)\n* ''[[Attack (1956 film)|Attack]]'' (1956)\n* ''[[Edge of the City]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[Saint Joan (1957 film)|Saint Joan]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[The Pride and the Passion]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[The Young Stranger]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[Bonjour Tristesse (film)|Bonjour Tristesse]]'' (1958)\n* ''[[Cowboy (1958 film)|Cowboy]]'' (1958)\n* ''[[Vertigo (film)|Vertigo]]'' (1958)\n* ''[[The Big Country]]'' (1958)\n{{col-break}}\n* ''[[Anatomy of a Murder]]'' (1959)\n* ''[[North by Northwest]]'' (1959)\n* ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[Spartacus (film)|Spartacus]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[The Facts of Life (film)|The Facts of Life]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[Exodus (1960 film)|Exodus]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[Ocean's 11]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[West Side Story (1961 film)|West Side Story]]'' (1961)\n* ''[[Something Wild (1961 film)|Something Wild]]'' (1961)\n* ''[[Advise & Consent]]'' (1962)\n* ''[[Walk on the Wild Side (film)|Walk on the Wild Side]]'' (1962)\n* ''[[The Victors (film)|The Victors]]'' (1963)\n* ''[[Nine Hours to Rama]]'' (1963)\n* ''[[It's a Mad, Mad, Mad, Mad World]]'' (1963)\n* ''[[The Cardinal]]'' (1963)\n* ''[[In Harm's Way]]'' (1965)\n* ''[[Bunny Lake Is Missing]]'' (1965)\n{{col-break}}\n* ''[[Grand Prix (1966 film)|Grand Prix]]'' (1966)\n* ''[[Not with My Wife, You Don't!]]'' (1966)\n* ''[[Seconds (1966 film)|Seconds]]'' (1966)\n* ''[[Such Good Friends]]'' (1971)\n* ''[[That's Entertainment, Part II]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[Broadcast News (film)|Broadcast News]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Big (film)|Big]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[The War of the Roses (film)|The War of the Roses]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Goodfellas]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Cape Fear (1991 film)|Cape Fear]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Doc Hollywood]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Mr. Saturday Night]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[The Age of Innocence (1993 film)|The Age of Innocence]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Higher Learning]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Casino (film)|Casino]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[A Personal Journey with Martin Scorsese Through American Movies]]'' (1995)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Logos and other designs==\nBass was responsible for some of the best-remembered, most iconic logos in North America, including both the Bell Telephone logo (1969) and successor AT&T globe (1983). Other well-known designs were [[Continental Airlines]] (1968), [[Dixie Cup|Dixie]] (1969) and [[United Airlines]] (1974). Later, he would produce logos for a number of Japanese companies as well.\n\nSelected logos by Saul Bass and their respective dates (note that the links shown point to articles on the entities themselves, and not necessarily to the logos):\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[Alcoa]] (1963)\n*[[Ajinomoto]] (1973)\n*[[AT&T Corporation]] (1969 and 1983)\n*[[Avery International]] (1975)\n*[[Boys & Girls Clubs of America]] (1978)\n*[[Celanese]] (1965)\n*[[Continental Airlines]] (1968)<ref name=\"Serling\">Serling, Robert J. (1974). ''Maverick: The story of Robert Six and Continental Airlines''. Doubleday & Company. {{ISBN|0-385-04057-1}}.</ref>\n*[[Dixie Cup|Dixie]] (1969)\n*[[Frontier Airlines (1950\u20131986)|Frontier Airlines]] (1978)\n*Fuller Paints (1962)\n*[[Geffen Records]] (1980)\n*[[General Foods]] (1984)\n*[[Girl Scouts of the USA]] (1978)\n*[[Japan Energy Corporation]] (1993)\n*[[J. Paul Getty Trust]] (1993)\n*Kibun Foods (1984)\n*[[KOS\u00c9|Kose Cosmetics]] (1991)\n*[[Lawry's Foods]] (1959)\n*Minami Sports (1991)\n*[[Minolta]] (1978 and 1981)\n*[[NCR Corporation]] (1996)\n*[[Quaker Oats]] (1969)\n*[[Rockwell International]] (1968)\n*[[Security Pacific Bank]] (1966)\n*[[United Airlines]] (1974)\n*[[United Way of America|United Way]] (1972)\n*[[Postage stamps and postal history of the United States|US postage stamp]], \"Science and Industry\" (1983)<ref>[http://www.katranpress.com/stamps_bass_1_1.html \"A postage stamp by Saul Bass\"]. Retrieved 2011-04-02.</ref>\n*[[Warner Communications]] (1974)\n*[[Wienerschnitzel]] (1978)\n*[[Wesson Oil]] (1964)\n*[[YWCA]] (1988)\n{{div col end}}\n\nAn analysis of a sample of Bass's corporate logos in 2011 found them to have an unusual longevity. The most common cause of the end of a Bass corporate logo (in the selection analyzed) was the demise or merge of the company, rather than a corporate logo redesign. The average lifespan of a Bass logo is more than 34 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adage.com/article/behind-the-work/a-favorite-saul-bass-logos/241361/ |title=A Few of Our Favorite Saul Bass Logos |first=Rupal |last=Parekh |date=May 8, 2013 |work=[[Advertising Age]]}}</ref> In 2014, [[Frontier Airlines]] resurrected the stylized F logo originally designed for Frontier by Bass in 1978, and discontinued when the airlines when bankrupt in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://skift.com/2014/09/10/frontier-airlines-looks-to-the-past-to-set-designs-on-its-future// |title=Frontier Airlines Looks to the Past to Set Designs on Its Future|first=Brian |last=Sumers |date=September 10, 2014 |work=[[Skift]]}}</ref>\n\n==Movie posters==\n[[File:The Man with the Golden Arm poster.jpg|upright|thumb|''[[The Man with the Golden Arm]]'' poster designed by Bass]]\nSaul Bass designed emblematic movie posters that transformed the visuals of film advertising. Before Bass's seminal poster for ''[[The Man with the Golden Arm]]'' (1955), movie posters were dominated by depictions of key scenes or characters from the film, often both juxtaposed with each other. Bass's posters, however, typically developed simplified, symbolic designs that visually communicated key essential elements of the film. For example, his poster for ''The Man with the Golden Arm'', with a jagged arm and off-kilter typography, starkly communicates the protagonist's struggle with heroin addiction. Bass's iconic ''[[Vertigo (film)|Vertigo]]'' (1958) poster, with its stylized figures sucked down into the nucleus of a spiral vortex, captures the anxiety and disorientation central to the film. His poster for ''[[Anatomy of a Murder]]'' (1959), featuring the silhouette of a corpse jarringly dissected into seven pieces, makes both a pun on the film's title and captures the moral ambiguities within which this court room drama is immersed.\n\nHe created some of his best known posters for films directed by [[Otto Preminger]], [[Alfred Hitchcock]], [[Billy Wilder]], and [[Stanley Kubrick]] among others. His last commissioned film poster was created for [[Steven Spielberg]]'s ''[[Schindler's List]]'' (1993), but it was never distributed.<ref>Kirkham, Pat & Jennifer Bass (2011) ''Saul Bass: A Life in Film & Design'' (pp. 406 and 420). London: Laurence King</ref> His poster work spanned five decades and inspired numerous other poster and graphic designers. Bass's film posters are characterized by a distinctive typography and minimalistic style.\n\nSelected posters by Saul Bass, and their respective dates:\n\n===1950s===\n[[File:Vertigomovie restoration.jpg|thumb|upright|''[[Vertigo (film)|Vertigo]]'' poster designed by Bass]]\n* ''[[Carmen Jones (film)|Carmen Jones]]'' (1954)\n* ''[[The Man with the Golden Arm]]'' (1955)\n* ''[[Edge of the City]]'' (1956)\n* ''[[Storm Center]]'' (1956)\n* ''[[Love in the Afternoon (1957 film)|Love in the Afternoon]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[Saint Joan (1957 film)|Saint Joan]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[Bonjour tristesse (film)|Bonjour tristesse]]'' (1958)\n* ''[[The Big Country]]'' (1958) (style b poster)\n* ''[[Vertigo (film)|Vertigo]]'' (1958)\n* ''[[Anatomy of a Murder]]'' (1959)\n\n===1960s===\n[[File:AnatomyMurder2.jpg|upright|thumb|''[[Anatomy of a Murder]]'' poster designed by Bass]]\n* ''[[Exodus (1960 film)|Exodus]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[The Magnificent Seven]]'' (1960) (design not used)\n* ''[[One, Two, Three]]'' (1961)\n* ''[[Advise & Consent (film)|Advise & Consent]]'' (1962)\n* ''[[It's a Mad, Mad, Mad, Mad World]]'' (1963)\n* ''[[The Cardinal]]'' (1963)\n* ''[[In Harm's Way]]'' (1964)\n* ''[[Bunny Lake Is Missing]]'' (1965)\n* ''[[The Firemen's Ball]]'' (1967)\n* ''[[The Two of Us (1967 film)|The Two of Us]]'' (1967)\n* ''[[Why Man Creates]]'' (1968)\n* ''Very Happy Alexander'' (1969)\n\n===1970s===\n[[File:The Shining (1980).png|upright|thumb|''[[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]'' poster designed by Bass ([[The Shining (film)#Ad campaigns|which he intended to be red, but was changed by Stanley Kubrick to yellow]])<ref name=filmartgallery>{{cite web |url=https://filmartgallery.com/collections/the-shining |title=The Shining Vintage Movie Posters {{!}} Original Film Posters @ Film Art Gallery |website=filmartgallery.com |access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>]]\n* ''[[Such Good Friends]]'' (1971)\n* ''[[Rosebud (1975 film)|Rosebud]]'' (1975)\n* ''Brothers'' (1977)\n* ''Notes on the Popular Arts'' (1977)\n* ''Bass on Titles'' (1978)\n* ''[[The Human Factor (1979 film)|The Human Factor]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[The Solar Film]]'' (1979)\n\n===1980s and 1990s===\n[[File:Theatrical release poster (not distributed) designed by Saul Bass for the film, Schindler's List (1993).jpg|upright|thumb|''[[Schindler's List]]'' poster designed by Bass, his last commissioned film poster (not distributed).]]\n* ''[[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]'' (1980)\n* ''[[Return from the River Kwai]]'' (1989) (not distributed)\n* ''[[Schindler's List]]'' (1993) (rejected poster)\n\nHe received an unintentionally backhanded tribute in 1995, when [[Spike Lee]]'s film ''[[Clockers (film)|Clockers]]'' was promoted by a poster that was strikingly similar to Bass's 1959 work for Preminger's film ''[[Anatomy of a Murder]]''. Designer Art Sims claimed that it was made as an homage, but Bass regarded it as theft.<ref>Schaefer, Stephen (September 08, 1995). [http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,298637,00.html \"Poster Imposter\"]. ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''. 2011-04-02.</ref> Many film posters have been considered to be homages to Saul Bass's posters. Some recent examples include the theatrical release poster for ''[[Burn After Reading]]'' (2008) which incorporates Bass's typography and style of figurative minimalism,<ref>{{cite web|title=Burn After Reading Poster Inspired by Saul Bass|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/burn-after-reading-poster-inspired-by-saul-bass/|publisher=/Film|date=June 17, 2008}}</ref> and a poster for ''[[Precious (film)|Precious]]'' (2009) which includes elements from several of Bass's posters, including ''[[Anatomy of a Murder]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dieselation.com/?tag=saul-bass |title=Saul Bass |publisher=Dieselation |date=2009-05-30 |accessdate=2012-06-06}}</ref> The cover art for [[The White Stripes]]' single ''[[The Hardest Button to Button]]'' is clearly inspired by the Bass poster for ''[[The Man with the Golden Arm]]''.<ref>[http://www.voxpopmag.com/le-magazine/16961-sound-and-vision-the-white-stripes/ SOUND AND VISION: THE WHITE STRIPES-VoxPop]</ref>\n\nThe comic book artist [[J. H. Williams III]]'s designs for the [[Batman]] story [[Batman R.I.P.|\"The Black Glove\"]] pay homage to Bass's designs as well.<ref>Singer, Marc. ''Grant Morrison: Combining the Worlds of Contemporary Comics''. (Univ. Press of Mississippi, Jackson, MS, 2012) p. 272. [https://books.google.com/books?id=ZVB2LK-FAusC&pg=PA272 Link at Google Books].</ref>\n\nIn addition to movie posters, Bass designed numerous posters for film festivals, and several magazine, book, and album covers. He also designed five Academy Award Presentation posters and the [[Student Academy Award]] for the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]].<ref>[http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/about/awards/saa.html \"Student Academy Award\"]. Oscars.org. Retrieved 2011-12-20.</ref> In 1962 he illustrated his only children's book, ''Henri's Walk to Paris'', written by Lenore Klein.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grainedit.com/2007/12/03/henris-walk-to-paris-designed-by-saul-bass |title=grain edit \u00b7 Henri's walk to Paris : Designed by Saul Bass |publisher=Grainedit.com |date=2012-02-14 |accessdate=2012-06-06}}</ref>\n\n==Filmmaker==\nDuring the 1960s, Bass was asked by directors and producers to produce not only title sequences for their films, but also to visualize and storyboard key scenes and sequences within them. Bass has the unusual credit of \"visual consultant\" or \"pictorial consultant\" on five films. For ''[[Spartacus (film)|Spartacus]]'' (1960), Bass as \"visual consultant\" designed key elements of the gladiator school and storyboarded the final battle between slaves and Romans. [[John Frankenheimer]], the director of ''[[Grand Prix (1966 film)|Grand Prix]]'' (1966), had Bass storyboard, direct, and edit all but one of the racing sequences for his film. For ''[[West Side Story (1961 film)|West Side Story]]'' (1961) Bass filmed the prologue, storyboarded the opening dance sequence, and created the ending title sequence.<ref name=\"kirkham2011\"/>\n\nIt is Bass's credited role as \"pictorial consultant\" for Alfred Hitchcock on ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' (1960); however, that has caused some controversy and debate. Bass claimed that he participated in directing the highlight scene of ''Psycho'', the tightly edited shower-murder sequence, though several on set at the time (including star [[Janet Leigh]]) disputed this claim.<ref>[http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2014/02/20/psycho_shower_scene_directed_by_saul_bass_watch_storyboards_side_by_side.html/ Harris, Aisha (February 20, 2014) \"Did Saul Bass Direct the Shower Scene in ''Psycho''?\"] Slate.com. Retrieved 2014-2-23</ref>\n\nThe research of several film scholars on Hitchcock's production of ''Psycho'' validates the claim that Bass in his capacity as a graphic artist did indeed have a significant influence on the visual design and pacing of that famous scene. Hitchcock had asked Bass to design and produce storyboards for the shower murder scene and for some other scenes in the film. For this, Bass received a credit as Pictorial Consultant as well as Title Designer. Janet Leigh told [[Donald Spoto]] that \"the planning of the shower scene was left up to Saul Bass, and Hitchcock followed his storyboard precisely. Because of this ... [the shooting] went very professionally,\"<ref>Spoto, Donald (1999 [1983]). ''The Dark Side Of Genius: The Life Of Alfred Hitchcock''. New York: Da Capo Press. (pp. 454\u2013455)</ref> and she told [[Stephen Rebello]] that \"Mr. Hitchcock showed Saul Bass's storyboards to me quite proudly, telling me in exact detail how he was going to shoot the scene from Saul's plans\".<ref>Rebello, Stephen (1990). ''Alfred Hitchcock and the Making of Psycho''. New York: St. Martin's Griffin. (p. 102) {{ISBN|0-312-20785-9}}.</ref>\n\nBill Krohn has noted that Bass's 48 story board panels for the scene introduced all the key aspects of the final shower murder scene \u2013 most notably, the fact that the attacker appears as a silhouette, close-ups of a slashing knife, the shower curtain torn down, a shot of the shower head from below, Marion's desperate outstretched arm, and the famous shot of the transition from the drain hole of the bathtub to Marion Crane's dead eye. Krohn notes that this final transition is highly reminiscent of Bass's iris titles for ''[[Vertigo (film)|Vertigo]]''.<ref name=Krohn>Krohn, Bill (2003). ''Hitchcock at Work''. (pp. London: Phaidon Press. (p. 231)</ref> Krohn also concludes that Bass did not literally direct the shower scene, proving Hitchcock's presence on the set throughout the shooting of that scene.<ref name=Krohn/>\n\nBass introduced the idea of using a montage of fast cuts and tight framing to render a violent, bloody murder as an impressionistic and nearly bloodless one. Hitchcock felt uncertain about Bass's conception of the scene fearing that audiences might not accept such a stylized and quickly cut sequence. In an interview with film historian [[Pat Kirkham]], Bass recalled, \"Having designed and storyboarded the shower sequence, I showed it to Hitch. He was uneasy about it. It was very un-Hitchcockian in character. He never used that kind of quick cutting; he loved the long shot\".<ref name=\"kirkham2011\"/>\n\nTo convince Hitchcock that the scene would work as planned, eight days before shooting of the final shower scene, Bass used a newsreel camera and Janet Leigh's stand-in [[Marli Renfro]] to shoot footage on the set to plan the shots in more detail. Working with Hitchcock's editor [[George Tomasini]], he edited this footage following the storyboards to show Hitchcock how the scene could work. In the end, Hitchcock gave his approval but, according to Kirkham, made two additions: a spray of blood on the chest of Marion Crane/Janet Leigh as she slides down the tiles, and a close-up of her belly getting stabbed.<ref name=\"kirkham2011\"/>\n\nIn 1964, Saul and his wife and creative partner [[Elaine Bass|Elaine]] directed the short film ''The Searching Eye'' shown during the [[1964 New York World's Fair]], co-produced with [[Sy Wexler]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pyramidmedia.com/homepage/search-by-title/humanities/searching-eye-detail.html|title=HUMANITIES : Searching Eye, The|website=www.pyramidmedia.com}}</ref> The Basses also directed a short documentary film called ''[[Why Man Creates]]''<ref>[https://www.bcdb.com/cartoon/55396-Why-Man-Creates Why Man Creates (1968) Theatrical Cartoon - BCDB]</ref> which won the [[Academy Award for Documentary Short Subject]] in 1968.<ref>[http://nightflight.com/why-man-creates-saul-basss-short-film-on-the-nature-of-creativity/ \u201cWhy Man Creates\u201d: Saul Bass\u2019s short film on the nature of creativity\u2014Night Flight]</ref>  An abbreviated version of that film was broadcast on the first episode of the television newsmagazine ''[[60 Minutes]]''. In 2002, this film was selected for preservation in the United States [[National Film Registry]] by the [[Library of Congress]] as being \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/prn-02-176/librarian-of-congress-adds-25-films-to-national-film-registry/2002-12-17/|title=Librarian of Congress Adds 25 Films to National Film Registry|website=Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. 20540 USA}}</ref> Saul, in collaboration with his wife and creative partner [[Elaine Bass|Elaine]], directed several other short films, two of which were nominated for [[Academy Award]] Oscars; ''[[Academy Award for Best Live Action Short Film|Notes on the Popular Arts]]'' in 1977,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pyramidmedia.com/homepage/search-by-title/humanities/notes-on-the-popular-arts-detail.html|title=HUMANITIES : Notes On The Popular Arts|website=www.pyramidmedia.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/notes-on-the-popular-arts-v35724|title=Notes on the Popular Arts (1978) - Elaine Bass, Saul Bass &#124; Synopsis, Characteristics, Moods, Themes and Related|website=AllMovie}}</ref> and ''[[The Solar Film]]'' in 1979, the latter for which [[Robert Redford]] was the executive producer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pyramidmedia.com/homepage/search-by-title/academy-awards/solar-film-detail.html|title=ACADEMY AWARD : Solar Film, The|website=www.pyramidmedia.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thescienceofcreativity.com/653|title=The Science of Creativity - The Solar Film|website=www.thescienceofcreativity.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, Saul Bass made his only feature-length film as a director, the visually splendid though little-known [[science fiction film|science fiction]] film ''[[Phase IV]]'', a \"Quiet, haunting, beautiful, ... and largely overlooked, science-fiction masterwork\".<ref>Scalzo, Thomas (August 8, 2005). [http://www.notcoming.com/reviews/phase4/ \"''Phase IV'' (review)\"]. ''[[Not Coming to a Theater Near You]]'' (notcoming.com). Retrieved 2008-10-16.</ref> The moving image collection of Saul Bass is held at the Academy Film Archive and consists of 2,700 items. The film material at the Academy Film Archive is complemented by material in the Saul Bass papers at the Academy's Margaret Herrick Library.<ref>{{cite web|title=Saul Bass Collection|url=http://www.oscars.org/film-archive/collections/saul-bass-collection|website=Academy Film Archive}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nOn May 8, 2013, Bass's 93rd birthday was celebrated by a [[Google Doodle]], which featured the tune \"[[Unsquare Dance]]\" by [[Dave Brubeck]].<ref>[http://www.csmonitor.com/Innovation/2013/0508/Saul-Bass-Designer-artist-and-auteur-of-the-opening-credits \"Saul Bass: Designer, artist, and auteur of the opening credits (+video)\"] by Matthew Shaer, ''[[The Christian Science Monitor]]'', May 8, 2013</ref><ref>{{YouTube|64lDaAmpvSo|Doodle for Saul Bass' 93rd Birthday}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Portal|Biography|Film}}\n\n* [[Elaine Makatura Bass]]\n* [[Motion graphics]]\n* [[Paul Rand]]\n* [[Richard Amsel]]\n* [[Tom Jung]]\n* [[Frank McCarthy (artist)|Frank McCarthy]]\n* [[Bob Peak]]\n* [[Drew Struzan]]\n* [[Howard Terpning]]\n* [[Pablo Ferro]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Kirkham, Pat and Jennifer Bass (2011). ''Saul Bass: A Life in Film & Design''. London: Laurence King. {{ISBN|978-1-85669-752-1}}.\n* Tomislav Terek (2001). ''Saul Bass on Titles: Film Titles Revealed''. Defunkt Century. {{ISBN|1-903792-00-2}}.\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0000866}}\n*[https://filmartgallery.com/pages/saul-bass-archive Saul Bass Archive] at [https://www.filmartgallery.com FilmArt Gallery]\n*[http://www.saulbassposterarchive.com/ Saul Bass Poster Archive] The Saul Bass Estate\n*[http://www.notcoming.com/saulbass/index.php/ Titles Designed by Saul Bass (still sequences & commentary)]\n*[http://www.artofthetitle.com/designer/saul-bass/ Saul Bass Title Sequences on Art of the Title]\n*[http://www.37signals.com/svn/posts/917-title-sequences-from-saul-bass-the-master-of-film-title-design Title Sequences from Saul Bass (videos & commentary)]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2013/may/08/saul-bass-title-sequence-ten-best?CMP=EMCFLMEML1672 Saul Bass title sequences: ten of the best] compiled by ''The Guardian''\n* [http://catalog.oscars.org/vwebv/holdingsInfo?bibId=68170 Saul Bass papers], Margaret Herrick Library, Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bass, Saul}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:AIGA medalists]]\n[[Category:American graphic designers]]\n[[Category:American typographers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in California]]\n[[Category:Deaths from lymphoma]]\n[[Category:Directors of Best Documentary Short Subject Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Film and television title designers]]\n[[Category:Film poster artists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American artists]]\n[[Category:Logo designers]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:James Monroe High School (New York City) alumni]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn College alumni]]\n", "name_user": "68.179.161.107", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(REMOVED UNTRUE INFO)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saul_Bas